<FIRST>r a PM-EnrollmentEnticement     09-16 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Enrollment Enticement,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Use Prizes To Boost Attendance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools offered free pizza, door prizes and even
chauffeured transporation to lure students to class for a head count
that will determine the size of state aid payments.
   At Parkman Middle School, Principal Dennis Schumacher gave away
portable radios, movie tickets and restaurant certificates. Victory
elementary school invited parents to a picnic.
   The idea was to get as many youngsters as possible in school
Friday, the day set by the state for deciding its per-student
distribution of financial assistance among districts throughout the
state.
   Milwaukee school district spokesman David Begel said Thursday's
enrollment figure was about 96,500. Official figures for Friday were
to be announced Monday.
   The Milwaukee Public School District expects to get $2,300 per
student.
   At Burdick school, principal Robert Schleck arranged to have one
youngster chauffeured to and from school, saying he was a transfer
from another school and had not yet been assigned a bus route.
   Robert Peters, principal at Custer High School, urged each
student to ``bring a dropout to school.''
   ``I told them that it was an excellent way for each of them to
help their peers have a better future,'' Peters said.
   School officials spent the last two weeks tracking students who
did not show up on opening day with telephone calls and visits to
their homes.
   On opening day at Vincent High School, 400 fewer students than
expected showed up, principal Kery Kafka said. Since then,
enrollment has increased by 210, enough to ensure that the school
will not lose any teachers, she said.
</TEXT>
