<FIRST>r a PM-Names     09-16 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theater critics stung Sting for his stage debut
in ``The Threepenny Opera,'' but some in the black-tie audience
found the British pop star's performance dazzling.
   ``Slow and turgid stuff,'' complained The Washington Post's David
Richards, who said Sting's ``acting has little resonance and his
singing voice is surprisingly thin.''
   Sting said that President and Mrs. Bush, who watched from box
seats above the National Theater stage Thursday night, congratulated
him backstage on his performance. Sting played Mack the Knife in the
pre-Broadway premiere of Bertolt Brecht's biting musical satire.
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin, who joined Bush backstage during
an intermission, said he was delighted with the play. He also seemed
to appreciate the chance to talk with Bush. The curtain for the
final act was delayed when the two men stepped aside for an animated
conversation alone.
   ``We didn't know if we were going to have a peace treaty ending
the Cold War or a third act,'' one cast member said later.
   The show is scheduled to open at the Lunt-Fontanne Theater in New
York on Nov. 5 after a four-week run at the National.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. says he'll fight
throat cancer with radiation treatments and without cigarettes.
   The 63-year-old singer, dancer and actor said he's been a heavy
smoker since he was 14. He quit 10 days ago.
   ``I'm going cold turkey,'' Davis said. When the urge strikes, ``I
put something else in my mouth. Candy, Life Savers, anything.''
   Davis said the prognosis for his recovery is strong. ``It's just
radiation, not cutting, so the voice box won't come out. Thank God
it's localized in one area,'' he said Thursday night from Lake Tahoe.
   A throat abnormality was detected recently during Davis' annual
medical examination and was diagnosed as cancer by Dr. Joseph
Sugerman, Davis spokesman Arnold Lipsman said. Sugerman expects
Davis to recover completely from the cancer, Lipsman said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Downey Jr., who encouraged abuse from
his audience as a television talk show host, will be trying to
tickle funny bones in his new role as a country singer on a TV
sitcom.
   SYS Entertainment Group Inc., a newly formed company based in
central Florida, announced that Downey also will return as a TV talk
show host and on a drive-time radio program.
   SYS President Dennis Richard said the company is offering for
syndication ``That's My Dad,'' in which Downey will star as a
country singer living in Nashville, Tenn., with his three daughters.
The company also is trying to syndicate the talk show, called
``America Talks with Morton Downey Jr.''
   Downey's old TV show, canceled in July by MCA Television after
declining ratings, often was trashed by critics.
   ``I was always a kinder, gentler Mort, but the critics never saw
it,'' Downey, 55, said Thursday. ``But the audience always did.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Syracuse University students
angered by NFL Hall of Fame running back Jim Brown's comments about
women picketed a campus bookstore where he signed copies of his
book, ``Out of Bounds.''
   The students said Brown had made sexist comments in his book and
to a local newspaper columnist. Brown met with the students Friday
and later appeared with them at a conciliatory news conference.
   ``I feel very strongly about everything these students stand for
and as I travel I will make mention of these things,'' he said.
   ``All women should be respected. All people should be
respected,'' said Brown, who played for Syracuse between 1954-1956
and retired from the NFL's Cleveland Browns as the league's all-time
leading rusher.
   Brown's comments ``were things about younger women being better
than older women, that women don't need an education, about women's
role in marriage,'' said senior Amy DiGennaro.
   Brown apologized for the remarks, but did not recant them.
   ``My personal preference is my personal preference,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former heavyweight boxing champion Joe
Frazier plans to handle the hits with his voice instead of his fists
when he returns to the stage next month in Atlantic City.
   Frazier is taking his rhythm-and-blues act to the Claridge Hotel
&amp; Casino on Oct. 6 and 7.
   ``I've been doing it off and on for years and years,'' Frazier
said.
   Frazier recently was in a car accident that caused soreness in
his back and legs. He may wear a neck brace for the performance,
which also will star friend Sonny Averona.
   Smokin' Joe said he remembers singing with his family in church
and outside his house at Friday and Saturday night barbecues.
   ``We all sang together,'' Frazier said. ``Mama, if you didn't
strike a note right in church, she'd say, `What's wrong with you?'
when you'd get home.''
</TEXT>
