<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     09-16 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashrita Furman bounced 13 miles on a pogo stick
to celebrate his 35th birthday, and dedicated the apparently
record-breaking hop to his guru.
   ``I used to be a totally unathletic nerd, but then I got involved
in meditation,'' said Furman, whose birthday is today. His guru is
Sri Chinmoy. According to the 1988 Guinness Book of World Records,
Furman holds the previous record for distance pogo-jumping (11.3
miles) and for pogoing under water (3 hours and 40 minutes beneath
the Amazon in Peru.)
   Furman, a New York native, said he bounced 10 miles around a
running track in a park Friday, then bopped up Third Avenue three
miles to the Empire State Building, wearing out two heavy-duty pogo
sticks during the day.
   The building's managers were unmoved by Furman's record-breaking
plans and refused him permission to hop up the skyscraper's steps.
Furman set the earlier distance record by pogo-ing up and down
Japan's Mount Fuji.
</TEXT>
