<FIRST>u w AM-CaspianEarthquake     09-16 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caspian Earthquake,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Occurs in Caspian Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake has occurred in the Caspian
Sea several hundred miles from the site of a quake that killed
thousands in Soviet Armenia last year, the U.S. Geological Survey
says.
   The tremor occurred at 10:05 p.m. EDT Friday about 90 miles east
of Baku, the capital of Soviet Azerbaidzhan, Don Finley, a spokesman
for the USGS here, said early today.
   Monitors at the National Earthquake Information Service in
Golden, Colo., measured the quake at 6.6 on the Richter scale,
Finley said.
   There were no reports of casualties or injuries, although an
earthquake of that magnitude has potential to cause severe damage,
said Finley.
   About 400 miles east of the epicenter of the tremor, a quake
measuring 6.9 on the Richter scale killed about 25,000 people in
Soviet Armenia last Dec. 7.
</TEXT>
