<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-Drugs Bjt   09-16 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Drugs, Bjt,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush `Flexible' as Drug Talks Start; Jackson Rips Drug Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, anxious for money to launch the
war on drugs, says he is ready to deal with Senate Democrats seeking
to expand the program by $2.2 billion now and enlarge it in the
future.
   ``We're flexible in terms of the funding method,'' Bush said at a
White House luncheon Friday. ``But I strongly believe we must return
the integrated elements of this drug strategy which took more than
six months to develop.''
   His comment came as a Senate bipartisan task force came away from
two hours of negotiations Friday with Republicans promising to
present a fresh financing plan when talks resume Monday.
   Meanwhile, the Rev. Jesse L. Jackson told the House select
committee on narcotics the Bush plan ``does not match the breadth of
this social crisis'' and urged summit-style talks to draw up a new
version.
   In the Senate, the Democratic plan to generate an additional $2.2
billion through a half-percent, across-the-board cut in federal
programs remained part of a money bill for transportation programs
awaiting final floor action.
   The administration opposes the idea, offered by Senate
Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., which
would slice $1.8 billion from the Defense Department's budget.
   ``We can't afford to sacrifice our military preparedness,'' Bush
said Friday.
   Democrats were confident following the initial session of the
task force made up of nine Republican and nine Democratic senators.
``It was a good step,'' Byrd told a news conference.
   Democrats said, however, that money agreements reached now would
be only a start on the drug war and that they have fundamental
disagreements with the Bush administration over what its size and
scale should be.
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del.,
said Democrats eventually want to expand the attack on cocaine
dealers beyond what has been envisioned thus far by Republicans and
provide more treatment and education.
   National drug policy director William J. Bennett, author of the
drug plan, says it most likely will be expanded in the future and an
updated version is due in February. He also says the
administration's request is a sharp increase over a drug-fighting
budget that was only $2 billion three years ago.
   Jackson drew applause and scattered shouts of approval from
spectators as he told the House select committee on narcotics the
nation needs ``a new initiative equal to the scope and depth of the
problem.''
   He criticized the plan for lack of enforcement strength, aid for
the poor and input from national and community leaders with
experience in fighting drugs. He said a meeting at the Camp David
presidential retreat should be convened to redraw the strategy.
   Jackson was sharply critical of both Bennett and the president.
   ``In April, Mr. Bennett announced that he would take
comprehensive emergency action to attack the drug crisis in the
nation's capital,'' Jackson said. ``Five months later, we still have
the emergency but no action.''
   ``President Bush announced a drug plan for Bogota, Colombia.
Where is his plan for the District of Columbia and cities around the
nation?'' he said.
   Jackson, reported to be weighing a race for mayor of Washington,
suggested the nation's capital could be a model for fighting the
drug scourge. He was asked what his role in that effort would be.
``A volunteer,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
