<DOCNO> AP890916-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-QuickAIDSTest Bjt   09-16 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quick AIDS Test, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>New AIDS Test Gives Results, On The Spot, In 10 Minutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients worried they may be infected with the
AIDS virus will be able to get a quick and confidential answer soon
with a simple test that takes only 10 minutes.
   The test, now undergoing trials at nine centers, will enable
people to get results quickly in a doctor's office instead of having
to wait to hear from a distant laboratory.
   ``It provides a new means for patients to learn of their AIDS
status and still retain anonymity,'' said Jarel R. Kelsey, president
of Murex Corp., a Norcross, Ga., firm that developed the test.
``Once this method is widely available, it will encourage more
people to determine their status.''
   Tests for AIDS now require that blood be drawn and sent to a
laboratory for complex processing. Patients must wait to find out if
they have contracted the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, which
causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or AIDS.
   ``That can take a number of days sometimes,'' said Kelsey.
   Concern about whether the test information will be kept
confidential and the long wait for results discourage some people
from being tested for AIDS, even though they may be at risk for the
disease, he said.
   The new test, called SUDS for single use diagnostic system, takes
away some of that anxiety.
   It consists of a small plastic disk, slightly thicker than a
camera lens cap, that is filled with an absorbent material. A
cone-shaped indention on top leads down to a small hole that exposes
the absorbent material.
   A SUDS test starts with a blood sample obtained from a simple
finger stick. Two drops of serum, the clear fluid in blood, are
separated from the sample and then combined with two reactant
solutions. The mixture is poured into the cone of the test cartridge.
   Inside the tester, the sample mixture is absorbed and pulled
through a color reactant. If a dot on the bottom of the disk remains
white, there is no AIDS virus. A blue dot means an AIDS infection.
The whole process takes about 10 minutes.
   Kelsey said the system works through the use of microscopic latex
beads that are coated with proteins that react to AIDS antibodies.
An antibody is a molecule in the blood produced by the body's immune
system to attack specific invaders, such as bacteria or virus. The
proteins used in SUDS react to antibodies created by the immune
system in response to both the outer membrane and the core of the
HIV virus.
   SUDS is being tested at selected doctors' offices, sexual disease
clinics, hospitals and blood banks. The trials started in July and
more than 5,000 tests have been conducted.
   ``The trials so far have shown an average accuracy rate of 99.8
percent,'' said Kelsey. ``Any specimen that has evidence of AIDS
antibody has been detected by the system so we are really achieving
levels of 100 percent sensitivity.''
   Clinical trials of SUDS end in October and the Food and Drug
Administration is expected to approve a license quickly, Kelsey said.
   FDA spokesman Brad Stone said the agency does not announce its
intentions ahead of time and will have to study the data. But he
noted, ``We recognize the need to get any test for AIDS out as soon
as possible.''
   Although the SUDS test is very simple to conduct, Kelsey said it
will not be sold for home use.
   ``Everybody is aware that exposure to the HIV is a terminal
condition,'' he said. ``Having that information revealed without
counseling immediately available could be a traumatic experience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
