<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Pierce     09-16 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Pierce,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Likely Faces Subpoena; One Lawmaker Wants Special Prosecutor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for Samuel Pierce says he'll try
to convince a House subcommittee not to subpoena the former housing
secretary, but lawmakers say Pierce's refusal to appear voluntarily
leaves them no choice.
   The chairman of the panel investigating abuses at the Department
of Housing and Urban Development said Friday he would ask members to
approve a subpoena next week. Republicans joined majority Democrats
in saying they would support the request.
   Pierce's attorney, Paul Perito, said he would try to convince the
subcommittee next week to give Pierce two weeks to prepare and then
allow him to testify voluntarily.
   In another development, Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., asked the
House Judiciary Committee on Friday to ask Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh to name a special prosecutor and have a grand jury
investigate actions at HUD during Pierce's tenure. There was no
immediate action on the request.
   The House Government Operations subcommittee on housing and
employment subcommittee denied Perito's request Friday for a
two-week extension for Pierce to testify.
   ``I am at a loss to understand why there is such a concern for
speed over truth,'' said Perito.
   Pierce told the subcommittee Thursday evening he would not appear
the next morning, prompting a number of verbal attacks from the
panel's members.
   ``We have no option but to proceed in teaching Mr. Pierce that
while he may run, he may not hide,'' said subcommittee Chairman Tom
Lantos, D-Calif.
   ``Not only is Silent Sam silent, apparently today he's also
invisible,'' added Rep. Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens, R-Ohio, using the
derogatory nickname Pierce acquired for his low-profile demeanor as
secretary during the Reagan administration.
   The subpoena vote is scheduled for Wednesday, but it was unclear
when the panel would demand that Pierce appear.
   Perito said Pierce most likely would comply with any subpoena but
left open the possibility of fighting an order if it gave Pierce
less than two weeks to prepare.
   ``You can be assured that I will consider all options,'' Perito
said.
   The panel is investigating allegations that prominent Republicans
and former HUD officials got favored treatment from the agency under
Pierce, some making huge profits as consultants obtaining
multimillion-dollar federal housing contracts.
   The department also is still unable to account for millions of
dollars in connection with projects and home sales during Pierce's
eight years as secretary. Critics blame poor management.
   Justice Department officials have said more than 1,000
HUD-related cases are being reviewed by U.S. attorneys around the
country, and there have been a handful of criminal and civil cases
filed in recent months.
 
