<FIRST>r w PM-AutoDefects     09-16 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Defects,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Upgrades Ford Seat Belt Probe, Opens Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is intensifying its
investigations of possibly defective seat belts in Ford Aerostar
vans and of bus arm rests blamed for injuries to nine people in a
New Jersey accident.
   The National Highway Transportation Safety Administration also
announced a new investigation Friday of Mazda seat belts and 10
other new investigations of cars, mobile homes, utility vehicles and
motorcycles made by Chevrolet, Pontiac, Yamaha, Jeep, Porsche,
Jaguar, Isuzu, Lincoln, Mobile and Kawasaki.
   Such investigations are used to determine whether to order a
recall of the vehicles.
   The agency said it had upgraded its examination of Aerostars
manufactured between 1986 and 1988 from a paperwork analysis to an
engineering analysis, which involves studying the allegedly
defective parts.
   The NHTSA opened a preliminary evaluation in December 1988 after
receiving seven complaints of fraying front-seat, passenger-side
seat belts.
   ``Something sharp is rubbing against the belt, apparently,'' said
agency spokesman Tim Hurd.
   The agency conducted a survey and detected other cases of fraying
but no injuries resulting from the problem, Hurd said, adding,
``We're always concerned about seat belts. They double your chances
of surviving a head-on collision.''
   In Detroit, Ford spokeswoman Joy Stinson said 450,000 Aerostars
were built between 1986 and 1988. Of those, 338,000 were equipped
with a plastic cover that shields the seat belt from contact with
the metal hinge, Ms. Stinson said.
   Belt fraying is believed to be limited to vans without the
plastic cover, which the company began installing in 1987 to protect
the hinge and improve the seat's appearance, she said.
   NHTSA also said it was upgrading to an engineering analysis a
probe of 1988 Motor Coach Industries inter-city buses. The National
Transportation Safety Board requested a preliminary evaluation June
5 after a bus crashed in Tinton Falls, N.J. Nine passengers were
hurt when arm rests broke, leaving sharp edges.
   Also, the agency began a preliminary inquiry into other arm rests
made between 1984 and 1989 by Wakefield International Seating Inc.,
the manufacturer of the Motor Coach Industries seat rests.
   The Mazda probe is of seat belts in all cars the company
manufactured between 1984 and 1989 following 11 complaints of 15
injuries resulting from failure to restrain passengers in accidents.
   NHTSA also reported launching preliminary evaluations of:
   _Breaking buckles on Chevrolet Camaros and Pontiac Firebirds
built in 1984 through 1986. The probe covers an estimated 500,000
cars.
   _Malfunctioning throttle grip sticks on 1989 Yamaha FZR400 and
FZR600 Yamaha motorcycles. The probe covers 10,000 cycles.
   _Malfunctioning rear seat belts in Jeep Cherokees, Wranglers and
Wagoneers. The probe covers the 1984 through 1988 model years.
   _Smoke and fires under the dashboards of 1987 Porsche 924 and
Porsche 944 models covering 7,500 cars.
   _Anti-lock brake system failures in 1987 through 1989 models of
the Jaguar XJ6.
   _Ball-joint failures in 50,000 1988 Isuzu Impulses after three
complaints of collapsed front suspensions causing loss of vehicle
control.
   _Power-steering failure in 1988 Ford Lincoln Continentals,
covering 40,000 cars.
   _Detaching spare tire mounts on Mobile Class A motor homes,
covering about 7,000 vehicles from 1988 and 1989.
   _Detaching handlebars on 1,000 Kawasaki ZX-7 motorcycles from
1989.
</TEXT>
