<FIRST>r w PM-US-Refugees     09-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Refugees,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Urges Other Nations to Take in Soviet Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is calling on other
nations to ease the burden on the United States by taking in some of
the recent surge of emigres from the Soviet Union.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger issued the call
Friday as he defended the Bush administration from criticism that a
proposal to allow 50,000 Soviet refugees into the country in the
next year is too conservative.
   ``I resent the implication that we have some heartless,
niggardly, conservative approach to this problem,'' Eagleburger told
the Senate Judiciary subcommittee on immigration.
   ``But there are limits on the numbers we can take,'' he said,
citing budgetary constraints and the press of refugees worldwide
seeking to come to the United States.
   ``No budget deficit, however large, should ever induce the United
States to abandon or compromise in any way its fundamental values
and principles'' of granting safe haven to ``oppressed peoples,''
said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the subcommittee, said
the months of administration deliberations on its Soviet refugees
strategy had given the impression that ``you're dealing with cans of
beans rather than human beings.''
   Some 150,000 applications for entry _ mostly from Jews and some
Pentacostals _ are expected in the 1990 fiscal year. Critics say
that leaves the administration's quota figure too low.
   For nearly 20 years the demand for liberalized Soviet emigration
was a cornerstone of U.S. policy, but ``never was it said that the
U.S. has an obligation to take them all in'' if the gates open,
Eagleburger said.
   He said Western Europe, Israel, Canada and Australia should also
offer entry to the Soviets, although he conceded attempts to enlist
the other countries' help over the past few months had not borne
fruit.
   ``I can't tell you there will be a massive willingness on the
part of other countries,'' he said, ``but we'll continue trying.''
   Under existing procedures, most Soviet emigres leave the Soviet
Union with Israeli visas but change course for the United States
once they reach processing centers in Rome and Vienna. Only about 10
percent to 15 percent go to Israel.
   To save money, the administration will shut down the Rome and
Vienna facilities once it clears up the backlog of an estimated
30,000 applicants there, and process all applicants in Moscow after
Oct. 1, Eagleburger said.
</TEXT>
