<FIRST>r a PM-RunawayTruck     09-16 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaway Truck,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy In Different Place At Right Time _ Misses Being Hit By Runaway
Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Makel Wright's night away from his usual
position in front of the TV set saved him from being hit by a
runaway fire truck.
   The 11-year-old Gainesville boy likes to spend each night playing
the Nintendo game on a television set in his bedroom. But Thursday,
his older brother took the television to college with him,
interrupting Makel's nocturnal habit.
   The boy was in another room when the truck crashed through the
bedroom wall Thursday night, his mother said.
   ``This is a miracle,'' said Clairese Wright. ``It demolished my
baby's room. Thank God he was not in bed. I thank you Jesus that
child was not in that bed.''
   Police Capt. Bill Taylor said the fire truck answered a call on a
steep hill near the Wright's home in Gainesville, about 40 miles
northeast of Atlanta.
   Fireman Boone Simmons said he was spraying the fire when he felt
his fire hose jerk. He and some bystanders chased the vehicle, which
rolled down the street, crashed into the Wrights' car, plunged
through their front porch and rammed into the house.
   It wasn't the first time a vehicle had smashed into the Wrights'
house. Last April, a car ran into their porch.
</TEXT>
