<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez Bjt   09-16 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez, Bjt,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Halts Spill Cleanup, Governor Praises `Good-Faith Effort'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a sun-drenched day, Exxon pulled out its
cleanup crews for the winter and the state announced its own plan to
protect fish hatcheries and untainted areas from the Exxon Valdez
oil spill.
   ``It's a nice day for the first day of winter, isn't it?'' Gov.
Steve Cowper said Friday before he announced the state's plans for a
$21 million program ``to continue cleanup work left by Exxon.''
   But for that bit of sarcasm, and a crack by his spokesman about a
``dirty dozen of soiled beaches'' left by Exxon, Cowper was
conciliatory toward the oil company responsible for the March 24
tanker wreck that left 10.9 million gallons of crude oil in Prince
William Sound.
   The governor thanked the thousands of workers who helped scrub
the oil-fouled shorelines, proclaiming Friday ``Oil Spill Workers
Appreciation Day'' in Alaska.
   Exxon pulled the crews out Friday, saying Alaska's early winter
makes continuing field work too risky.
   ``I think Exxon has made a good-faith effort to clean up the
beaches,'' Cowper said. ``I'm not going to fault Exxon here. They
made some mistakes and, frankly, some of the things the state has
done were mistakes.''
   Cowper said the state should have known how to clean up a major
spill. ``At least we should have known no one else knew how to do
it,'' he said.
   Alaska's winter program, announced on a warm fall day when
residents donned T-shirts and shorts, calls for:
   _Small-scale cleanups when fish and wildlife resources are
threatened by the remaining oil.
   _Monitoring the oil's movement and changes in its composition
during the region's severe winter months.
   _Research and development of new ways to remove the remaining
oil, most of which lies under the surface of rocky shorelines.
   _Protecting the region's five fish hatcheries with standby
equipment and crews.
   _Forming a strike force of counselors and mental-health
professionals to help prevent and treat stress-related problems,
such as drug and alcohol abuse, in spill-affected towns.
   Money for the program will come from the state's new
5-cent-a-barrel oil-spill response tax. Cowper said Exxon eventually
will be billed for reimbursement.
   While Cowper had little negative to say about Exxon, he showed
reporters a seven-minute, state-produced video that focused on the
oiled shores the company has vacated. On a nearby table were oiled
rocks taken this week from what a Cowper spokesman said were soiled
beaches.
   Exxon spokesman Henry Beathard said later that the beaches where
surface oil remains visible were the last treated with a chemical
fertilizer. The fertilizer, which stimulates the oil-eating action
of microorganisms, takes up to six weeks to work.
   State environmental officials are worried about the subsurface
oil. They fear winter storms and tidal action will loosen that oil,
resulting in small slicks that will pollute other areas.
   Although Exxon has promised to monitor the oil and respond to
emergencies during the fall and winter, Cowper said it remained
unclear to what extent the company will work with the state.
   Exxon has said it will re-evaluate the shorelines next spring and
decide then whether to resume the cleanup on a large scale.
   The governor noted that some biologists alleged recently that
Exxon's cleanup, which employed as many as 12,000 workers, may have
done more environmental harm than good.
   ``That may be,'' Cowper said. ``But what was Exxon going to do?
Not only was everyone barking at them to get it done, including us,
they had a public relations problem.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
