<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-16 0730</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kelly Urges Arabs To Drop Campaign Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official is calling
on the Arab governments to abandon their efforts to expel Israel
from the United Nations.
   That ``change in tactics'' could contribute to attempts to
arrange negotiations between the Arabs and Israel, John H. Kelly,
assistant secretary of state for the Near East, said Friday night.
   ``It is time for the Arab nations to follow the example of the
PLO and acknowledge Israel's existence as a state. Israel is
entitled to membership in the United Nations under the principle of
universality,'' Kelly said in a speech before a conference on the
Middle East at Wye Plantation in Maryland.
   He referred to the step taken last year by Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman Yasser Arafat, who also publicly renounced
terrorism. That action met U.S. conditions for the dialogue opened
by the United States with the PLO last December.
   ``It is time for the Arab governments to stop the anachronistic
practice of voting against Israeli credentials,'' Kelly said.
   The Arabs have consistently failed to oust Israel from the United
Nations despite annual attempts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Library of Congress May Become Computer Accessible</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An improved computer network could make the
huge store of information in the Library of Congress available to
libraries and scholars across the country, says the nation's chief
librarian.
   ``The Library of Congress and the national library community want
to help develop a national research and education network,'' James
H. Billington, the librarian of Congress, told a Senate subcommittee
Friday.
   ``The major information resources for this nation reside in the
Library of Congress and other research libraries across the country.
These collections have been assembled in many cases with federal,
state and local revenues.
   ``Our citizens have a right to expect that these irreplaceable
intellectual resources be made ever more widely available through a
national information network,'' he said.
   Billington testified in favor of a bill sponsored by Sen. Al
Gore, D-Tenn., which calls for the establishment of national
computer-based research network. Gore chairs the Senate Commerce
science subcommittee, which held Friday's hearing.
   The Library of Congress, with 88 million items, is the largest
collection of recorded and printed information ever assembled in a
single place, Billington said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Administration Retreats On Plan To Aid Ortega's Foes</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has bowed to
congressional pressure and abandoned its idea of aiding the
presidential election campaign of Nicaraguan opposition leader
Violetta Chamorro through a U.S.-financed private organization.
   While the National Endowment for Democracy should play an active
role in ensuring a free and fair election, the United States will
not ask the group to go beyond election activities permitted by its
charter, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Friday.
   Chamorro is campaigning to defeat Daniel Ortega, the Nicaraguan
president, in a national election next February. All U.S. efforts,
including past weapons shipments to anti-government rebels known as
Contras, have failed to unseat the Sandinista leader.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III ran into stiff opposition
when he sounded out members of Congress earlier this week about
providing around $2 million in U.S. funds to Chamorro, the publisher
of the leading opposition newspaper, La Prensa, through the
endowment.
   Boucher said the group's charter permits it ``to support election
activities in a general sense. We don't intend to ask it to do
anything that's beyond its charter.''
   The group gets its money from Congress.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>League of Cities President Asks for Big Hike in Drug-Fighting</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Budget
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal drug-fighting budget for 1990
should be increased by $5 billion to $6 billion over the
administration's proposed $7.9 billion and taxes should be raised to
pay for it, says National League of Cities President Terry Goddard.
   Goddard, the Democratic mayor of Phoenix, Ariz., said Friday he
knows of no other way to get the new resources needed.
   The administration strategy will call on state and local
governments to spend $10 billion to $12 billion for drug testing and
prisons next year alone.
   ``We believe that an equivalent resource from the federal
government has got to be committed,'' Goddard said.
   He said he is asking municipal leaders to lobby Capitol Hill,
where some members of Congress already are balking at a proposal by
Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., to increase the $7.9 billion by $2.2
billion.
