<FIRST>u i AM-CaspianQuake 1stLd-Writethru a0416 09-16 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caspian Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quake Rocks Caspian Shore, Cracks Buildings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake rocked the Soviet Union's
Caspian Sea area early today, cracking some buildings but apparently
causing no serious damage or injuries, seismologists reported.
   The quake occurred at 6:05 a.m. and was centered in the Caspian
Sea about 110 miles east of Baku, the capital of Soviet Azerbaijan,
said Nadezhda Molchanova, a spokeswoman for the Obninsk Seismic
Station near Moscow.
   The Caspian Sea separates the Caucasus Mountain region and Soviet
Central Asia, two active seismic areas. A powerful quake Dec. 7 in
western Armenia, about 370 miles west of today's quake, killed
25,000 people.
   Monitors at the U.S. National Earthquake Information Service in
Golden, Colo., measured the quake at 6.6 on the Richter scale. The
Armenian earthquake registered 6.9 on the Richter scale, a gauge of
the energy released by a temblor, as measured by the ground motion
recorded on a seismograph.
   A quake measuring 6 can cause severe damage and a temblor
measuring 7 can cause widespread, heavy damage.
   Ms. Molchanova said there were no immediate reports of
casualties. She said the quake registered 7 on the Soviet earthquake
scale in Krasnovodsk, a city on the eastern shore of the Caspian Sea
in Soviet Turkmenia.
   The Soviet scale is based on observable effects of an earthquake.
A quake registering 7 is regarded as ``very strong,'' capable of
making cracks in stone walls.
   It registered at 5 in Baku, strong enough to wake the sleeping
and shake furniture.
</TEXT>
