<FIRST>u i PM-Canada-Arrests Bjt   09-16 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Arrests, Bjt,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Suspects Under Tighter Guard After Weapons Case Linked
to Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICTON, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Colombians accused of drug
smuggling have been moved to a more secure prison after being linked
to five heavily armed South Americans who were arrested near the
Maine border, officials said.
   Authorities on Friday declined to say if the five men, arrested
Wednesday, had planned to interfere with court proceedings for the
Colombians.
   But asked if the two cases were related, Inspector Al Hutchinson
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Fredericton said, ``That's
correct.''
   ``We've re-evaluated the situation between the two groups,'' he
said without elaborating.
   Hutchinson said the connection prompted police to move the
Colombians from the Fredericton jail to a more secure prison within
the province. He would not say which prison.
   At a court hearing in Fredericton Thursday, the two were ordered
held for trial next month on charges of smuggling a half-ton of
cocaine in the nose of an airplane. It was the largest seizure of
cocaine by Canadian police.
   The five South Americans, arrested in Edmunston, 125 miles
northwest of Fredericton, had Venezuelan passports.
   But in Washington, Frank Shults of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration said two were `known to be Colombians.''
   The agency sent several agents to Canada on Friday to discuss the
case with Canadian authorities, Shults said.
   Fredericton police said they were seeking up to three others in
the case.
   Canadian police ruled out suggestions the five arrested were
hired killers sent by Colombian drug traffickers to murder U.S. or
Canadian officials or to attack President Bush's vacation home in
Kennebunkport, Maine.
   In Washington late Friday, Secret Service spokeswoman Jane
Vezeris said, ``We do not believe it has anything to do with threats
to individuals in this country.''
   The United States has sent Colombia $65 million in aid, including
military equipment, for its month-old crackdown on the nation's drug
cartels, which provide most of the cocaine sold in the United States.
   Canadian and American officials say the cartels increasingly are
smuggling drugs through Canada's maritime provinces because the
United States has tightened its borders.
   When Mounted Police and Edmundston authorities arrested four of
the South American men, a search of their vehicles uncovered an Uzi
submachine gun, Soviet and Israeli assault rifles and 3,000 rounds
of ammunition. Also seized were six automatic pistols, a .22-caliber
pistol, tear gas, a deactivated Japanese grenade and an electric zap
gun used to knock people out.
   On Friday, police led the four handcuffed into a heavily guarded
provincial court in Edmundston, where they were charged with a
variety of weapons offenses.
   ``Innocent, innocent. Je suis innocent,'' one of the men told
reporters outside the courthouse.
   ``No speak English,'' said another.
   Authorities have identified the four as Tito Sanchez, Euovio
Manzano, Osvaldo Gonzales and Wilmer Ramon Zanabria. Court documents
did not contain their ages or hometowns.
   They were being held for bail hearings set for Tuesday.
   A fifth man, William Jose Rodriguez of Caracas, Venezuela, was
arrested Thursday in another provincial city. He was charged Friday
in Saint John with possessing two .22-caliber handguns. Authorities
said they expected to charge him later with an immigration offense.
   Rodriguez was being held until a bail hearing Monday.
   The Colombians accused of cocaine trafficking, Jose Ali
Galindo-Escobar and Fernando Augusto Mendoza-Jaramillo, both 36,
were arrested in April after police found about 1,100 pounds of the
drug inside the nose of an airplane at a makeshift airstrip outside
Fredericton.
</TEXT>
