<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DC-10-Safety Bjt   09-16 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10-Safety, Bjt,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Modifications to Be Made on DC-10s Following Iowa Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonnell Douglas Corp. says it will make
changes in its DC-10 jetliners to guard against failure of all three
hydraulic systems, the ``one in a billion'' condition in a DC-10
crash in Iowa that killed 112 people.
   The modifications were greeted warmly Friday by James B. Busey,
the head of the Federal Aviation Administration.
   ``The system design changes proposed by McDonnell Douglas ... are
a solid step forward in assuring there will be no repeat of the July
19 accident,'' Busey said in a statement issued in Washington, D.C.
   ``Once these design changes are in place, they will raise the
already high safety standards required of the DC-10 and, in effect,
make a good airplane even better.''
   The three hydraulic systems on the DC-10 are designed to operate
independently and to back each other up in case one fails. Unlike
some other plane models, the 400 or so DC-10s in use around the
world have no backup system if the hydraulic lines fail to control
the wing and tail mechanisms that steer the plane.
   ``We view the new enhancements as extra safety equipment similar
to the installation of air bags in automobiles _ additional measures
to protect occupants besides the lap belts, shoulder harnesses,
padded dashboards, etc.,'' said Dale Warren, a vice president of
Douglas Aircraft Co.
   Warren, who headed the company's investigation of the Sioux City,
Iowa, crash, said Friday modifications will include:
   _An electrically operated shutoff valve that will be installed in
the supply line and a check valve in the return line of the No. 3
hydraulic system.
   _A check valve installed in the No. 3 hydraulic reservoir.
   _A cockpit light added to alert the crew if the shutoff valve is
activated.
   The new fast-acting shutoff valve, located just behind the back
wall of the cabin, will close automatically and the cockpit light
will come on if a sensor detects hydraulic fluid dropping below a
preset level in the reservoir.
   Even if all three hydraulic systems are affected by severe damage
to the tail section, as happened in Sioux City, the valve will stop
fluid flow through the No. 3 system, Warren said.
   With adequate hydraulic pressure preserved in that system, the
crew should have enough control to fly the plane to a safe landing,
he said.
   In the July crash, the tail engine on the DC-10 disintegrated,
knocking out all three hydraulic systems _ an event with a ``one in
a billion'' chance of occurring, according to a McDonnell Douglas
release Friday.
   The pilot lost virtually all control of the plane, which exploded
in flames in a corn field after cartwheeling down the runway.
   Douglas Aircraft Co., a division of McDonnell Douglas based in
Long Beach, manufactured the DC-10s, which will eventually be
replaced by the more advanced but similar MD-11s.
   McDonnell spokeswoman Elayne Bendel said in a telephone interview
that the company had yet to decide whether to make the same
modifications to its MD-11s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
