<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0403EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneTalks     09-16 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Talks,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Telephone Contract Negotiations Broken Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NYNEX Corp. and its striking workers broke off
contract talks early this morning after a day of on-again, off-again
negotiations to end the six-week strike.
   ``Nothing was resolved, and no more negotiating sessions have
been scheduled,'' said Adele Stacy of Local 2222 of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   Negotiators for the telephone company and the IBEW met
intermittently Friday morning and afternoon, and union leaders said
the company appeared to be pushing to reach a settlement by
midnight. But the talks at Boston's Park Plaza Hotel ended
fruitlessly at 12:25 a.m.
   Earlier in the day, ebullient union leaders addressing 700
strikers at a rally outside New England Telephone Co.'s headquarters
in Boston said the six-week strike had been significantly
strengthened by a Massachusetts ruling that the workers would be
entitled to unemployment benefits starting next week.
   Myles Calvey, head of the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers Local 2222, estimated that unemployment payments for 12,000
Massachusetts workers would cost the telephone company $9 million
per week.
   Calvey and Steve Early, spokesman for the Communications Workers
of America, said the ruling Wednesday by the state Division of
Employment and training had caused the company to push for a rapid
settlement.
   NYNEX reportedly made concessions on safety and insurance issues
this week in its talks with the IBEW and the CWA, which together
represent 62,000 striking workers at NYNEX companies in New York and
New England.
   Workers walked out Aug. 6 after NYNEX asked them to start paying
$10.27 a week toward health insurance. For nearly 20 years, the
company had paid 100 percent of the insurance premiums.
   Job security, safety, wages and benefits are also on the
bargaining table, but both sides have said health care is the key
issue.
   ``It was our hope that (the strike) would have ended sooner,''
said Robert O'Brien, spokesman for NYNEX in New York. ``Our hope is
that we'll find a way out of this. We know our workers want to come
back to work.''
   NYNEX is the only one of the nation's seven ``Baby Bell''
regional telephone operating companies that still has not reached a
settlement with its workers. Employees of Bell Atlantic, Pacific
Telesis and Ameritech struck last month but reached agreements.
   Beginning next week, the more than 40,000 NYNEX strikers in New
York also will be eligible for unemployment compensation, said Early.
   Union leaders introduced a plan to help support 6,000 strikers in
other New England states who are not eligible for unemployment
benefits.
</TEXT>
