<SECOND>PM-Writer Shot,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Science Writer Shot During Dispute With Female Companion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORANGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A science writer underwent brain surgery
after being shot during a dispute with his female companion, a
hospital spokeswoman said.
   Thomas Heppenheimer, 42, author of several science books
including ``Earthquake'' and ``Man-Made Son,'' was in stable
condition late Friday, said Nancy Rhomburg, nursing supervisor for
the University of California, Irvine Medical Center.
   He had been listed in critical condition Thursday, following
surgery for two gunshot wounds to the head and a wound to the
shoulder, but was stabilized by Friday, Ms. Rhomburg said.
   Police believe Angela Lee Johnson shot Heppenheimer at the home
they shared in nearby Fountain Valley after he tried to attack her
with a 3-foot-long rod.
   Johnson, 30, who said she has lived with Heppenheimer for 10
years, was questioned by police and later released, said Fountain
Valley Police Lt. Mike Hanrahan.
   ``There is a strong case for self-defense,'' Hanrahan said.
   No charges have been filed, he said. The Orange County District
Attorney's Office is reviewing the case.
   Heppenheimer worked at the California Institute of Technology in
Pasadena in the 1970s before turning to science writing, institute
spokesman Bob Finn said.
