<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador     09-16 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monthly Talks Set Between Government And Rebels; 10,000 March In
Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY4, NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels and the Salvadoran government
have agreed to monthly peace talks aimed at ending nearly a decade
of civil war.
   After negotiators announced the agreement in Mexico City Friday,
an estimated 10,000 Salvadorans marched in their capital in support
of the plan.
   The guerrilla group, Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front,
said it hoped ``that 1990 will be the year of the war's final end.''
   ``The blood that has been spilled in the longest and most costly
conflict on the continent, all this blood that has been spilled,
deserves this,'' rebel leader Shafick Handal said at a news
conference in Mexico City.
   Since the fighting began in 1979, 70,000 Salvadorans have been
killed.
   In San Salvador, President Alfredo Cristiani called the agreement
important but said: ``While welcoming the dialogue process, we don't
want to create false expectations.''
   ``We want to reiterate that our attitude is one of openness and
flexibility within our constitutional framework ... We know the road
ahead is difficult and complex,'' he told an Independence Day rally.
   The rebels and the rightist government agreed to meet next in San
Jose, the Costa Rican capital, on Oct. 16-17 and once a month
thereafter.
   They agreed that two representatives from the Roman Catholic
Church will mediate the talks and that they will also invite the
United Nations and the Organization of American States to send
observers.
   The Cristiani government initially opposed church mediation or
outside observers. It had also proposed meeting the guerrillas every
two months instead of once a month.
   The pact, reached after two days of talks, also stipulates that
neither side can unilaterally withdraw from the negotiations and
that each delegation will have authority to reach binding accords.
   The Mexico City talks were the first in two years between the
government and rebels; they were also the first meeting between the
guerrillas and Cristiani's administration.
   The rebels have already laid out their peace proposal. The
government is to present its plan in October.
   The rebels are offering to lay down their arms and form a legal
political party in exchange for sweeping social and political
reforms. They dropped previous demands for power sharing and for
merging the rebel and government armies.
   Most of the civil war's victims have been civilians. Human rights
groups and international organizations say many were killed by
right-wing death squads linked to the military and Cristiani's
party, links the party denies.
   Washington has provided more than $3.5 billion in military and
economic aid to El Salvador this decade, making it Latin America's
biggest single recipient of American assistance.
   For the first time since the civil war started in 1979,
Salvadoran authorities staged an Independence Day military parade
through their capital on Friday. About 3,000 troops from the three
military branches and the three militarized police forces marched to
music by military bands.
   Crowds lined the parade route, which followed a route different
from that of the peace march. But the peace marchers appeared to
attract more people, who waved white flags and blue-and-white
national banners and chanted slogans hailing the peace talk
agreement.
   The march was sponsored by the National Debate for Peace, an
umbrella organization comprising about 70 church, union, student and
humanitarian organizations.
</TEXT>
