<HEAD>Security Beefed Up For Bush's Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secret Service increased security for
President Bush's daughter but refused to say why.
   Reporters on Friday saw several agents escorting Dorothy Bush
LeBlond, who usually travels without security, from her office at
the Greater Portland Chamber of Commerce into a parked vehicle.
   Agents who had been at the building since noon indicated they
would continue their surveillance at the LeBlond home in Cape
Elizabeth.
   A woman at the home, however, said throughout the evening that
the president's daughter was not there and would take calls at her
office in the morning.
   Secret servicemen declined to comment on any connection between
the increased surveillance and reported threats against U.S.
officials by Colombian drug lords.
   ``I can't comment on that,'' spokeswoman Jane Vezeris said,
citing a Secret Service policy of not commenting on operational
matters. But she added:
   ``Something happened up there today, incident is too strong a
word, that caused the Secret Service to take action. ... We're
looking at it.''
   She said it was best described as a ``local police matter.''
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk also declined to respond on
grounds that the White House doesn't comment on security matters.
