<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Bird     09-16 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Bird,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rare Bird Sighting on Remote Islands Starts Travel Scramble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUMBURGH, Shetland Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of British bird
spotters headed for the Shetland Islands after their Birdline
telephone information service reported the presence of a rare great
knot wading bird.
   The bird spotters, nicknamed twitchers and armed with powerful
binoculars, telescopes and expensive cameras, compete among
themselves to log sightings of rare birds around Britain.
   The great knot is an Asian bird measuring just over 10 inches in
length.
   Birdline reported that one was seen Friday at a spot called the
Pool of Virkie near Sumburgh airport on the southern tip of the
remote Shetland Islands, 100 miles off Scotland.
   The British domestic news agency Press Association reported that
it was the first recorded sighting of a Great Knot in Britain and
only the fourth for the whole of Europe.
   The news agency said previous European sightings were in Spain in
1979 and Denmark and East Germany in 1987.
   Birdline said the great knot is thought to have been blown off
course by easterly winds while migrating from its breeding grounds
5,000 miles away in northeast Siberia to its winter range, mainly in
southern China, Indonesia and Australia.
   Many bird watchers were expected to be frustrated in their bid to
reach the Shetland Islands by the weekend.
   One veteran twitcher, Ian Mills, from Whitburn in northeast
England, reported: ``The word has gone round that all flights to
Shetland tomorrow (Saturday) are booked solid so it looks as if the
majority of us will miss out this weekend.
   ``It's very frustrating that such a crowd-pulling bird should
have turned up at such a hard-to-get-to place.
   ``This is one of those once-in-a-lifetime opportunities. If it
had appeared on mainland Britain, thousands of people would have
been along to see it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
