<FIRST>r i PM-NuclearDisarmament     09-16 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Disarmament,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Nuclear Disarmament Symposium Starts in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international symposium on peace and security
through nuclear disarmament in the Asia-Pacific region opened today
with criticism that the region was lagging behind efforts in Europe,
officials said.
   Meeting spokesman Kenichi Nakamura said 31 scientists from 12
countries, including the United States, Soviet Union and Britain,
were meeting at the Pugwash Conference.
   It was started 34 years ago in Pugwash, Canada, at the suggestion
of Albert Einstein.
   Discussions at the meetings, most of which are closed sessions,
will focus on political and economic issues and how they effect
prospects for nuclear disarmament in the Asia-Pacific region,
Kenichi said.
   Yoshikazu Sakamoto, a professor at Tokyo's Meiji Gakuin
University, said during a keynote speech that the nuclear
disarmament movement in Europe has worked much harder than that of
the Asia-Pacific region.
   The major focus in the region has been disarmament at sea, which
is more difficult to accomplish than on land, he said.
   Sakamoto said disarmament would promote economic growth and
contribute to democratization of the Third World.
   Following three days of closed meetings, participating scientists
will report on the outcome of the conference Tuesday.
</TEXT>
