<HEAD>Two Students Arrested At High School Bush Visited</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two students at a rural high school that
President Bush visited early in his anti-drug campaign have been
arrested on drug charges, officials said.
   A spokeswoman for the Lancaster County Drug Task Force said
Friday the students, both 17-year-old girls, were arrested Thursday
at their homes and have been turned over to juvenile authorities.
The students' names were not released because of their ages.
   One was charged with two counts of delivery and one count of
possession with intent to deliver LSD, according to the spokeswoman,
who spoke on condition of anonymity. The youth had 579 doses with a
street value of $4 each.
   The second youth was charged with criminal conspiracy to deliver
marijuana and had about a quarter pound of the drug, the spokeswoman
said.
   The spokeswoman said the two were arrested as part of a two-month
undercover operation.
   ``We just happened to be doing our investigation and (the youths)
just became involved,'' she said. ``It did not center on the high
school.''
   Bush spoke to about 3,000 students at Conestoga Valley High
School in March and stressed the threat drugs pose to rural areas.
   The youths were selling drugs to people throughout Lancaster
County, known for its large population of Amish, mostly to users in
their late teens or early 20s, the spokeswoman said.
