<FIRST>u i PM-MotherTeresa 1stLd-Writethru a0454 09-16 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mother Teresa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fever Gone But Doctors Looking For Cause of Infection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with statement from hospital; pickup
5th graf pvs: `But Dr.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa was feeling better today
after a persistent fever disappeared, said a Roman Catholic nun at
the mission founded by the Nobel laureate in Calcutta's slums.
   But doctors still were trying to find the cause of an infection
that posed a new danger to Mother Teresa, 79, as she tried to
recover from a heart attack, said the nun, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Nonetheless, the nun said, ``She is feeling much better today.
The fever is gone and her temperature is normal.''
   A statement issued by doctors at Woodlands Nursing Home, the
hospital where she was admitted nearly two weeks ago, said Mother
Teresa's condition had improved and that she was responding to
treatment and ``resting calmly.''
   But Dr. Vincenzo Bilotta, a heart specialist from Rome and a
longtime friend of Mother Teresa, said her condition remained
serious.
   ``Her heart is very weak. The infection is now posing a new
danger to her,'' said Bilotta, who treated Mother Teresa for a
similar ailment in 1985.
   Dr. George Lombardi, an infectious disease specialist from
Cornell University in New York, said doctors were trying to find the
cause.
   ``We are doing everything possible but could not yet diagnose
it,'' he said. Lombardi and Bilotta flew to Calcutta earlier in the
week to help with the treatment.
   Mother Teresa developed chest pains and a high fever Thursday
just as doctors thought she was progressing well.
   She was admitted to the hospital Sept. 5 with an irregular
heartbeat, a blocked artery and high fever. She suffered a heart
attack three days later.
   ``We have hopes that she will recover and overcome this,'' said
Bilotta, who planned to return to Italy this weekend.
   Born in Yugoslavia, Mother Teresa gave up a comfortable life as a
convent teacher to live and work among the poor and dying in this
eastern Indian city's filthy slums. She was awarded the 1979 Nobel
Peace Prize for her work.
   She founded the Missionaries of Charity in October 1950 in an
abandoned run-down hostel donated by the city. The order, which was
formally recognized by the Vatican in 1965, expanded and now has
3,000 nuns working in 87 countries.
</TEXT>
