<FIRST>r a PM-MineExplosion     09-16 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mine Explosion,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blowtorch May Have Triggered Explosion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANFIELD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators suspect that a blowtorch
probably caused an explosion that killed 10 miners, but the probe
has been delayed while dangerous levels of methane are cleared from
the mine, authorities said.
   State inspectors found the blowtorch Friday near the site of
Wednesday's explosion, which officials believe to have been fueled
by methane gas, said Willard Stanley, commissioner of the Department
of Mines and Minerals.
   Workers may have been using the torch to disassemble a longwall
mining, investigators said.
   Officials of the U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration
approved a modified company plan to reduce the methane levels at the
William Station mine that delayed the investigation Friday, said
administration spokeswoman Kathy Snyder.
   Stanley said one of the mine's curtains _ used to channel outside
air to mining areas to carry away methane gas _ appeared to be
dislodged. Stanley said he didn't know if the curtain was moved out
of place before the blast, by the explosion itself or during rescue
operations.
   On Friday night, hours after the first burial of the mine
disaster, scores of area residents gathered for a memorial service
at Union County High School.
   ``In Kentucky, our families are strong. Our communities are
supportive, and our courage is abundant,'' Gov. Wallace Wilkinson
told the crowd, which packed the 700-seat auditorium. ``The events
are irreversible.
   ``We can only share in the immense grief.''
   A funeral service was held earlier for 31-year-old Mark Hedges.
The other burials were scheduled for today and Sunday.
   Also Friday, the head of a public-interest law firm said the mine
owner, Pyro Mining Co., and federal officials had failed to prevent
the disaster despite abundant warning signs. He said the government
had been too lenient with the mine owners.
   ``There's strong evidence that there was knowledge on the part of
both company and the government that there was a methane problem at
the mine, coupled with a ventilation problem,'' said J. Davitt
McAteer, executive director of the Washington-based Occupational
Safety and Health Law Center.
   Federal inspectors briefly shut down the mine seven times this
year because of imminent dangers, McAteer said.
   Pyro had reported 267 accidents at the mine since 1985 but failed
to report several others, said McAteer.
   MSHA spokesman Frank O'Gorman angrily denied McAteer's claim that
his agency had not properly policed Pyro.
   The agency imposed many penalties on the company, O'Gorman said.
   Company spokesman Ed Calman refused to discuss Pyro's safety
record, but denied criticism from area residents that Pyro was
withholding information about the accident. ``This company is not
hiding anything,'' Calman said.
</TEXT>
