<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-16 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Falls in Central Appalachians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms extended across the eastern Ohio Valley
and much of the middle Atlantic Coast region today and produced
heavy rain across the central Appalachians.
   Showers and thunderstorms in southeastern Kentucky brought 2.6
inches of rain to Virgie, and 1.7 inches fell in three hours in
Scott County, Va., Friday evening.
   Clouds and light rain lingered across the remainder of the Ohio
Valley into the middle Mississippi Valley.
   Flash flood watches were posted Friday night for western West
Virginia, southeastern Kentucky and southwestern Virginia, and
remained in effect today for much of West Virginia, western Maryland
and northwestern Virginia.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were fairly numerous from North
Carolina to northern Florida. Wind associated with a late evening
thunderstorm downed trees and power lines near Lexington, S.C.,
which also had flooding.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 a.m. EDT
included 2{ inches at Roanoke, Va., more than 2 inches at Mary
Esther, Fla., and about 1{ inches at Valparaiso, Fla., Charleston,
W.Va., and Greensboro, N.C.
   Clouds and light rain showers spread across Southern California
this morning. Farmers in California's San Joaquin Valley were told
to watch out for rain, which would hinder the drying of the raisin
crop.
   Today's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms scattered from
the Florida peninsula across the middle and southern Atlantic Coast
states, and the central and southern Appalachians to the eastern
Ohio Valley. Rain showers also should be scattered over western
Washington.
   Highs were expected in the 60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast
and from the upper and middle Mississippi Valley across the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys and the Great Lakes to the northern Atlantic
Coast; in the 90s in Florida, southwest Texas, the northern High
Plains, and from the southern Plateau into California's interior
valleys; from 100 to 105 degrees in the desert Southwest and in the
80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 88 degrees at Phoenix. The
nation's high Friday was 107 degrees at Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Other reports:
