<FIRST>r a PM-ZsaZsaTrial     09-16 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Outspoken Celebrity To Clam Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in Zsa Zsa Gabor's
cop-slapping trial ordered the outspoken celebrity to quit talking
to the news media in defiance of a gag order.
   ``I will make a warning, but this will be the first and last time
I say this,'' Municipal Court Judge Charles Rubin told Miss Gabor on
Friday.
   ``You are to say to the press, `No comment.'''
   The judge's warning, after a contempt of court request from a
prosecutor, was based on earlier statements by Miss Gabor. Rubin
apparently was unaware of Miss Gabor's catty remarks a few moments
before in the corridor outside court, in which she blasted Beverly
Hills Police Officer Paul Kramer, the motorcycle cop who arrested
her.
   The former Hungarian beauty queen told reporters she should have
scratched Kramer's eyes out.
   ``I think that cop is not too bright,'' Miss Gabor said. ``I
think he must be very spoiled because he's very sexy. He's gorgeous.
He's sexy, but I don't like that man.''
   Miss Gabor's diatribe had begun at the curb, where she alighted
from her Rolls-Royce in a black-and-white Anne Klein trouser outfit
and a furious mood.
   ``This man is the biggest liar and the Police Department is the
biggest liar in the world,'' Miss Gabor said, ignoring pleas from
her attorney reminding her of the gag order.
   After Rubin's warning, defense attorney William Graysen
complained about a television interview with another Beverly Hills
police officer who called Miss Gabor a ``foul-mouthed, cheap
lawbreaker.''
   Miss Gabor remained closemouthed during the proceedings and
passed time sketching a portrait of the bailiff and displayed it to
reporters in the court during a brief bench conference.
   Miss Gabor, who says the doodling ``calms my nerves,'' previously
drew pictures of the judge, the clerk and the court reporter.
   Kramer pulled her over on June 14 for having expired registration
tags on her Rolls-Royce. As he checked for other violations, Miss
Gabor allegedly drove off, was stopped again, and allegedly slapped
Kramer's face.
   She is charged with misdemeanor battery on a police officer,
disobeying an officer's orders, driving with an expired license and
car registration, and having an open container of alcohol in her car.
   Kramer, who testified on Thursday that Miss Gabor cursed, spit
and slapped him, left the stand in the morning after
cross-examination by the defense.
   Kramer was asked if he had worn a ``Free Zsa Zsa'' T-shirt at his
recent 38th birthday party and Kramer said he had.
   Asked if it got hot under his helmet, Kramer said it did.
   ``Does it ever fry your brain?'' Graysen asked, getting a ``no
comment'' from the officer and an objection from the prosecutor. It
was sustained.
</TEXT>
