<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0636EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     09-16 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Waste Agreement Reached; Nuclear Weapons Plant Remains Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant will remain
open over the weekend after federal officials reached a tentative
agreement on handling the plant's wastes, a federal official said.
   Negotiators for the Department of Energy, which owns the plant,
and Environmental Protection Agency in Washington, D.C., reached
agreement on the thorny issue Friday, said the official, who spoke
only on condition that he not be identified further.
   Plant operator Rockwell International Corp. had set a Friday
deadline for the DOE and the EPA to resolve conflicting regulations
concerning radioactive, hazardous and mixed wastes at the plant.
Sources had said the plant could have closed as early as 5:30 p.m.
Friday if the demands weren't met.
   DOE officials had threatened in July to close the plant due to a
fear they could face criminal charges over ongoing environmental
violations stemming from the wastes, for which there is no federally
approved disposal site.
   The plant, which is 16 miles northwest of Denver and employs
about 6,000 people, is the only one in the country that makes
plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons, and federal officials have
warned that a shutdown could endanger U.S. defense.
   The source said the agreement calls for mixed waste to be stored
``in an environmentally sound manner,'' for DOE to launch a program
to reduce the amount of waste being generated at Rocky Flats, and
for the agency to do everything possible to improve its capacity for
treating the waste.
   The source said the agreement reached by negotiators still must
be signed by top agency officials. The state of Colorado also
reportedly gave approval to the agreement, but Rockwell thus far is
not a party, the source said.
   ``This in no way is a grant of immunity for any past
violations,'' the source said, apparently referring to an
investigation under way into alleged illegal disposal of wastes and
of a possible coverup. FBI and EPA investigators raided Rocky Flats
on June 6, and a special federal grand jury is reviewing the case.
   Cathy Kaliniak, a DOE spokeswoman in Washington, said the agency
would have no announcement until Monday and Rocky Flats would remain
open until at least that time. She said talks were continuing, but
declined to discuss details.
   ``Rocky Flats is continuing to operate as normal,'' said Dennis
Hurtt, a Rockwell spokesman.
   Rockwell later issued a statement that said its officials met
with representatives of the DOE, EPA and Justice Department to
discuss the issue.
   ``Rockwell finds itself in a position where one agency of the
federal government (EPA) says it may take legal action against our
people at Rocky Flats and against the corporation (Rockwell) for
actions that we are required to perform under contract with another
agency (DOE),'' the Rockwell statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
