<FIRST>r i PM-Guatemala     09-16 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guatemala,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Ex-Candidate Responsible For Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested two men and began a
manhunt for a right-wing former presidential candidate suspected in
violence blamed for at least 34 deaths and the disappearances of
seven students.
   Federal Police spokesman Guillermo Mollinedo said at a news
conference Friday that Leonel Sisniega Otero, who ran for president
in 1982, was behind the terrorist violence.
   He said Sisniega, 64, was ``directing'' the violence but did not
elaborate.
   Police found five grenades, two AR-15 rifles and other evidence
at Sisniega's home linking him to the attacks, Mollinedo said.
   Authorities did not say what motive Sisniega or the other
suspects would have for participating in the violent incidents,
which began nearly two months ago.
   Police told reporters that Maximiliano Archila Pellecer, 44, and
lawyer Mario Roberto Martinez Pena, 46, were captured Thursday.
   ``They confessed that Sisniega Otero was the one directing the
operations,'' Mollinedo said.
   Authorities said Archila was the first captured, and told about
Martinez. Police said they found more grenades Martinez's car when
they apprehended him.
   Thirty-four people have died in terrorist violence since July 19.
   Three students and one professor at San Carlos University were
found dead from multiple gunshot wounds last Sunday after being
abducted. Three shoe repairmen were found dead Monday, also from
gunshot wounds, and their right hands had been severed.
   Dozens of bombings in Guatemala City have killed two people and
injured dozens of others. A political leader and influential
businessmen were assassinated.
   Over the past few days, 23 other people have been killed in
various incidents. Seven students are missing and presumed kidnapped.
   Until Friday, authorities said they had no suspects or motives in
the cases.
   Earlier in the week, President Vinicio Cerezo blamed unidentified
right-wing and left-wing ``extremists'' for the violence and
promised to use all the government's resources to stop the terrorism.
</TEXT>
