<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0723EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VietnameseVisit     09-16 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnamese Visit,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Woman's Trip to America Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman, whose pain from napalm bomb burns
became a lasting image of the Vietnam War, has indefinitely
postponed a trip to the United States due to health reasons.
   Phan Thi Kim Phuc decided to put off the trip she had planned
this month, said Merle Ratner, co-director of the Committee to
Welcome Kim Phuc.
   A black-and-white photograph of 9-year-old Kim, screaming with
agony as she ran nude down a Vietnamese road following an air raid
in 1972, was published throughout the world and was awarded a
Pulitzer Prize.
   ``Everybody remembers it,'' Ms. Ratner said Friday in a telephone
interview from her office in New York. ``It was the one enduring
image from the war.''
   What is not apparent in the photo, said Associated Press
Photographer Nick Ut, who took the picture, is that the girl's back,
neck and arm were charred ``like barbecue.''
   Ut, who fled Vietnam in 1975 and continues to work for the AP in
Los Angeles, was reunited with Kim in Havana in July, the first time
they had been together since Ut took her to a hospital that fateful
day.
   ``I would like to see her here,'' Ut said. ``But now I think the
Vietnamese government doesn't want her to come here. I wish she
would come here soon.''
   Kim, 26, developed diabetes while studying pharmacology in
Havana, Cuba, and has had so much difficulty with her eyesight and
ability to concentrate that she decided to change her course of
studies to English, Ms. Ratner said.
   ``If she came here, she'd have to put off her studies in English,
which begin in the fall,'' Ms. Ratner said.
   The trip probably has been postponed for a year or more, she said.
   Vietnam's communist government already had approved Kim's trip to
America and played no part in influencing her decision, Ms. Ratner
said.
   ``They were very interested in having her make it,'' she said.
``No one wanted her to jeopardize her health.''
   Ut's prize-winning picture was the reason Ms. Ratner and others
organized Kim's trip. The ad hoc Committee to Welcome Kim Phuc was
formed ``specifically to bring her here as a gesture of friendship
and reconciliation,'' Ms. Ratner said.
   ``She's a good representative,'' Ms. Ratner said. ``She's
articulate. She's not a (Communist) Party member. She's a young
peasant woman who happened to have become famous because of her
misfortune. And people want to meet her.''
   Last month, Ms. Ratner said she spent two days with Kim in
Havana, where the Vietnamese woman has been studying for the past
three years or so.
   ``She was in good spirits,'' Ms. Ratner said. ``She was
disappointed she would have to postpone the trip, of course. ... You
could tell she had trouble concentrating.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
