<FIRST>u i PM-ArabLeague     09-16 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab League,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Committee Calls For Immediate Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-man peacemaking committee
called for an ``immediate and comprehensive'' cease-fire in Lebanon
today as a first step in a settlement of the 14-year-old civil war.
   In a communique issued in Saudi Arabia, Morocco and Algeria,
whose foreign ministers make up the committee, the three countries
said that ``there can be no solution to the Lebanese crisis by
military means.''
   The cease-fire call was meant to ``spare the bloodletting, and to
spread security and stability and provide the propitious atmosphere
for national reconciliation.''
   The cease-fire demand was the first point in a seven-point peace
plan contained in the communique.
   A Lebanese security body to be headed by Lakhdar Ibrahimi, an
Algerian who is the committee's delegate to Lebanon, would supervise
the implementation of the cease-fire, the committee said.
   It would also supervise ships ``when information is received by
the committee that they are carrying arms and ammunition to any
party.''
   As soon as the security body began its work, the naval blockade
would be lifted and Beirut International Airport reopened, the
communique said.
   It asked all the belligerents in Lebanon to ``immediately cease
the use of arms by all means, whichever the party.''
   It called on all concerned states, and those who supported the
committee in its task, ``to work by all means to halt the flow of
arms to any one in Lebanon.''
   The committee invited the members of Lebanon's Parliament to meet
to prepare and discuss a ``charter for national reconciliation'' on
Sept. 30 after the cease-fire has been stabilized, the naval
blockade lifted and the airport reopened. The venue of the meeting
would be declared after consultations by Ibrahimi, the communique
said.
   Ibrahimi would be heading to Lebanon on Sunday to put the
decisions into effect, the communique added.
</TEXT>
