<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Jordan     09-16 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Jordan,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assailant Firing From Jordan Injures Two Israeli Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assailant opened fire on an Israeli army
patrol today from the Jordanian side of the border and slightly
wounded two Israeli soldiers, the military said.
   It said the soldiers came under fire near the settlement of
Ashdot Yakov at about 4 a.m. Ashdot Yakov is three miles south of
the Sea of Galilee. It was the second such attack in two weeks.
   An army spokeswoman said the assailant, who apparently acted
alone, fired from the eastern side of the Israeli security fence, or
from the Jordanian territory, and did not cross the border.
   Israel radio said the assailant apparently was a Jordanian army
soldier who abandoned his position, ran to the border and ambushed
the Israeli patrol, managing to fire about 30 rounds while hiding
behind a bush.
   The Israeli patrol returned fire and conducted searches, during
which six cartridge clips from a U.S.-made M-16 assault rifle were
found near the border, the military command said.
   The radio said the attack took place close to a Jordanian army
position and that an army combat jacket was found near the site of
the attack.
   One of the injured Israeli soldiers was evacuated to Rambam
Hospital in the port city of Haifa, the army command said. The other
soldier was treated at a nearby army clinic, the army command said.
   Both reportedly suffered shrapnel wounds.
   An Israel radio reporter who was at the site of the attack said
the Jordanians appeared to be ``in a lot of confusion, maybe even
panic. In the beginning, you simply saw them running here and there
without knowing what to do.''
   He said a Jordanian search party was organized two hours after
the attack.
   It was the sixth attack this year on Israel from along the
Jordan-Israel border.
   The most recent attack occurred Sept. 7, when several
Soviet-designed Katyusha rockets were fired from Jordan into Israel.
There were no injuries.
   Following that attack, Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
Jordan ``must work to prevent such acts...as they are responsible
for the acts.''
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens, also speaking after the incident,
said ``the Jordanian government is responsible for every terrorist
act originating on the Jordanian territory. We are asking the
government of Jordan to take action...to prevent such acts in the
future.''
</TEXT>
