<FIRST>u i PM-China-Deng 1stLd-Writethru a0446 09-16 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Deng, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Appears for First Time in Three Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with details of meeting. Adds byline.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping today appeared in
public for the first time in more than three months, looking tanned
and vigorous as he met an American professor at the Great Hall of
the People.
   Deng's 70-minute meeting with T.D. Lee, a Nobel prize-winning
physicist from Columbia University, was his first public appearance
since June 9, five days after the bloody military attack on
pro-democracy students and their supporters in Beijing.
   Hundreds, and perhaps thousands, of people died as troops shot
their way into the city en route to seizing Tiananmen Square from
student demonstrators.
   Since then, Chinese and foreign sources have reported Deng is
seriously ill with prostate cancer and may not have long to live.
Chinese officials have said Deng is in good health and spent part of
the summer resting at the seaside resort of Beidaihe.
   Speculation that Deng was no longer capable of carrying out his
official functions rose when he failed to meet the president of the
African state of Burkina Faso during a recent visit.
   The 85-year-old party patriarch, in remarks audible in an evening
news report on the meeting, said he sometimes swims for up to one
hour. ``I don't like indoor swimming pools, but enjoy swimming in
nature,'' he told the professor.
   The TV report showed the smiling Deng, wearing a gray Mao suit,
grasp Lee's hand with both of his and then walk steadily
hand-in-hand with the American. He was also shown in animated
conversation, gesturing and laughing.
   ``The recent turmoil has taught us a major lesson,'' Deng was
quoted as saying by the television news and by the official Xinhua
News Agency.
   ``Some of our comrades just immersed themselves in their specific
work, did not pay enough attention to ideological and political
developments, were not vigilant enough against the serious
corruption, and the measures taken to correct it proved less than
effective.''
   Deng was apparently referring to ousted Communist Party chief
Zhao Ziyang, who has been accused of abetting the pro-democracy
demonstrators and splitting the party.
   Deng stressed that China will not change the policies of reform
that he initiated a decade ago, but he also said China must stick to
socialism.
   ``There would be no new China today without the leadership of the
Communist Party,'' he said.
   Lee was a winner of the 1957 Nobel Prize for Physics.
</TEXT>
