<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     09-16 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>76 Dead In Three Days Of Sinhalese Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces have discovered 52 more
bodies in central Sri Lanka, bringing to 76 the number killed by
Sinhalese radicals in three days, the military said today.
   Elsewhere, soldiers Friday fatally shot 11 Sinhalese radicals and
arrested 226 others, said military officials.
   The officials said the 52 unidentified bodies had been found
since Friday in the villages of Kundasala, Menikhinna and Arangala
in central Kandy district, about 55 miles northeast of Colombo.
   The militants killed six Sinhalese civilians in three separate
attacks Friday, said the officials, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules.
   On Thursday, they said, 18 bodies with gunshot wounds were found
by security forces in the area.
   Authorities blamed the killings on the radical Sinhalese group
the People's Liberation Front, which is trying to overthrow the
Sinhalese-dominated government and which attacks civilians not
supporting its cause. Officials also accused militants of setting
fire to 30 homes.
   Sinhalese radicals oppose a July 1987 accord the government
signed in an attempt to end Tamils' war for a separate homeland. The
Sinhalese said the accord granted too many concessions to the
minority Tamils and compromised Sri Lanka's sovereignty by inviting
Indian soldiers to enforce the accord.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindu, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They say they are denied jobs and education by
the mainly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the
population and dominate the government and military.
   More than 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
been killed since the Tamil insurgency began in 1983. Five thousand
others have died in the Sinhalese backlash.
</TEXT>
