<FIRST>r a PM-MontanaTeachers 1stLd-Writethru a0426 09-16 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Montana Teachers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0426,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Strike Wrenching in Montana City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Kenczka, chairman...', to CORRECT governor's
name to Stan sted Dan Stephens.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREAT FALLS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She stood in the gutter outside C.M.
Russell High School in the chill morning sun of early fall, hugging
her craggy-faced biology teacher _ and crying for him.
   ``My teachers are my friends, and I support them,'' said
15-year-old Ann Gillin.
   Teacher Don Kenczka, the morning picket captain for strikers at
the school, is one of about 700 of the city's 720 teachers who have
been strike since Aug. 27. More than 500 substitutes have filled in
since classes began Sept. 5.
   ``I don't think this will end until they (the school board) see
these kids as we see them,'' said Kenczka, who returned the girl's
hug.
   Kenczka, chairman of the Russell biology department last year,
has been a teacher for 34 years. Ann, the granddaughter of Montana's
Republican Gov. Stan Stephens, refused to attend a substitute's
class, declaring to her parents that she would honor the picket line.
   The strike in this prairie city about 70 miles northwest of
Helena, the capital, has sharply divided the community's 60,000
residents.
   The only previous teachers strike in Great Falls was in 1975.
   ``Standing out here and watching somebody walk past you into your
classroom is like standing in your driveway and watching somebody
sleep in your bed,'' said Sharon, a fourth-grade teacher at
Riverview Elementary who declined to give her full name.
   The school board and the Great Falls Education Association remain
in disagreement over about 20 issues, including salaries, insurance
and transfer policy. Talks are continuing, haltingly.
   Frustration on all sides _ teachers, administrators, students,
parents _ is building into anger. Outside Great Falls High School,
one of the city's two high schools, teachers shouted ``Scab! Scab!''
recently at substitutes filing into the school.
   Some of the substitutes instinctively hunched their shoulders as
they passed the gantlet of strikers.
   Later, inside the high school, one of the substitutes called the
harassment ``terrorism.'' But most were quiet about their situation,
saying they didn't have time for an interview during school hours.
None of the substitute teachers took up invitations to talk later.
   At Great Falls High, female pupils repeatedly came to hug
striking teachers, and some cried. Grim-faced boys offered
encouragement and complained that the substitutes were incompetent.
   But many students who entered the school _ attendance has
increased gradually to more than 70 percent _ averted their eyes and
did not speak as they walked past the teachers.
   ``A lot of these kids need hugs,'' said Karol Johnson, principal
at Great Falls High.
   Johnson said she feels caught in the middle. She makes a point of
stopping to talk with the strikers each day. ``There are some of my
staff who will have a hard time forgiving me for that,'' she said.
   She helped negotiate the last three contracts, but declined to
get involved in the prickly talks this year. Recently, though, she
joined four secondary principals in sending a letter to the
superintendent urging a settlement.
   ``I want my staff back,'' she said. ``The subs are working hard,
but they are substitutes.''
   At Riverview, the mood was calmer. The strikers have a barbecue
grill in the parking lot. The young children often come to them at
recess to ask when they will come back, the teachers said.
   The teachers said it's hard explaining contracts to
kindergarteners. But, they said, the children understand the word
``fair.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
