<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0435 09-16 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0435,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops on Alert On Love and Friendship Day; Two Police Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with shooting in Bogota, troops on patrol
in major cities, air force reminder of policy to down suspicious planes.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers patrolled city streets today and
the air force reiterated orders to force down suspicious aircraft
following drug-related violence that killed two policemen on the eve
of a holiday celebrating love and friendship.
   As the nation observed the Day of Love and Friendship, army
soldiers on foot and in jeeps roamed Bogota, Medellin, Cali and
Barranquilla, Colombia's four biggest cities.
   On Friday, gunmen firing from a speeding car killed two police
officers in Bogota, police reported. Later Friday, assailants also
in a speeding car opened fire at the daily newspaper El Siglo,
police said. No one was injured in that attack.
   In the cocaine capital of Medellin, two policemen were wounded
when a bomb exploded near a police truck Friday. And in Cali, home
of another major cocaine cartel, three bombs wounded two policemen
and seven civilians, police said.
   They said another bomb found at a bus station was deactived.
   No one claimed responsibility for the attacks, but suspicion fell
on the nation's drug lords, who have been at war for a month with
the government.
   The Defense Ministry put the country's 200,000-man army and
80,000 national police on alert, canceling all leaves and keeping
the forces on standby.
   Bogota police chief Nasin Gianini Diaz said reports of
``telephone terrorism,'' in which callers make bomb and death
threats, increased in the capital on the eve of today's national
holiday, during which Colombians exchange gifts.
   ``Citizens should take the threats seriously and report them to
police,'' he said in an interview on Colombian television. ``But we
are guaranteeing a peaceful Day of Love and Friendship.''
   Armored trucks and army troops were sent to guard banks and
government buildings.
   Banks are frequent targets of the nation's powerful cocaine
traffickers. They have declared ``total and absolute war'' on the
government, which began a crackdown on trafficking after a leading
presidential candidate, Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, was assassinated
Aug. 18.
   As part of its effort to combat drug trafficking, Colombia's air
force issued orders 12 years ago for its pilots to force down
civilian planes that do not have permission to fly over Colombia.
   The air force commander, Gen. Alfonso Amaya, sent a copy of the
orders to the civil aeronautics agency Friday as a reminder of the
policy.
   The air force has forced down dozens of planes without flight
plans in the past 12 years but never has resorted to shooting down a
plane.
   Under emergency powers decreed by President Virgilio Barco,
authorities have confiscated hundreds of properties allegedly
belonging to drug kingpins and pledged to extradite drug suspects
wanted in the United States.
   So far, one person has been extradited, Eduardo Martinez Romero,
an alleged whiz financier for the Medellin cartel. He was flown to
Atlanta Sept. 6, where he is to stand trial on money laundering
charges.
   Two other drug suspects are being held in a maximum security
prison pending extradition to Detroit and to Tallahassee, Fla.
   Colombia's top cocaine barons have escaped capture, however.
   In the Canadian province of New Brunswick Friday, authorities
said they had linked five men arrested with an arsenal of weapons to
two Colombians accused of importing drugs into that country.
   The five men were carrying Venezuelan passports and were arrested
in Edmundston, New Brunswick, on Wednesday and Thursday.
   The Colombians, Jose Ali Galindo-Escobar and Fernando Augusto
Mendoza-Jaramillo, Thursday were ordered held for trial in
Fredericton, New Brunswick next month on charges of importing 1,100
pounds of cocaine.
</TEXT>
