<DOCNO> AP890916-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-NYCMayoral Bjt   09-16 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Mayoral, Bjt,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Koch: A Clash of Quieter Styles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One dresses like an undertaker and talks like a
diplomat; the other more resembles an ex-altar boy. Neither even
remotely takes after Edward I. Koch, the city's celebrated, reviled
and garrulous mayor since 1977.
   But one of them will take his job.
   The altar boy is Rudolph W. Giuliani, winner of last week's
Republican mayoral primary. His opponent is David Dinkins, who
toppled Koch in the Democratic contest with surprising ease.
   Whoever wins the general election, political analysts say the two
mark a new era of New York City politics. Giuliani is the first
Republican in 25 years with a shot at City Hall. Dinkins would be
the first black mayor.
   ``In a thematic way, New Yorkers are looking for change. The
voting in both primaries suggested that,'' said Raymond Harding,
chief of the city's tiny Liberal Party, whose nomination Giuliani
also holds. ``In the general election, change is the paramount
issue.''
   Giuliani hopes so. He is the ultimate political outsider, a
Republican in an overwhelmingly Democratic city, a former federal
prosecutor who made his name chasing corruption in city government
and Wall Street, a man who never has held elective office.
   ``Giuliani's principal asset is that he has no background in
government. Therefore he can say he's going to change things,'' said
Mitchell Moss, head of the Urban Research Center at New York
University. ``He can take the full offense: He says, `I'll clean
house.'''
   True to form, in accepting the GOP nomination Tuesday night,
Giuliani described his campaign as a ``crusade'' to establish ``a
new generation of leadership in this city.'' The next day he
personalized the attack, calling Dinkins a ``clubhouse politician''
tied to a discredited Democratic regime.
   Still, Giuliani, 45, faces formidable odds. Two-thirds of the
city's 3 million registered voters are Democrats. It took just
75,000 Republican votes for Giuliani to overwhelm his primary
opponent, cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder; Dinkins, to defeat Koch and
two other Democrats, got nearly 540,000 votes.
   ``This is a Democratic town with a vengeance,'' said Norman
Adler, a veteran political consultant. ``You've got to get a whole
lot of Democrats to vote for you if you want to win.''
   Dinkins, 62, has promptly seized that advantage, making party
affiliation a prime issue. ``New York will not become a Republican
beachhead in 1989,'' he declared Wednesday at a rally with his
defeated opponents. He personalized his attack as well,
characterizing Giuliani as an agent of ``reactionary Republican
government.''
   The two are likely to tangle on other issues, including legal
abortion, which Dinkins supports and Giuliani has addressed
equivocally; the death penalty, which Giuliani supports and Dinkins
opposes; and drugs and crime, on which Dinkins seeks to counter
Giuliani's crimefighting image.
   But neither is a Koch, whose acid tongue created issues as often
as it addressed them. Giuliani's first words Tuesday night were to
congratulate Dinkins and pledge ``a race that unites New York
City.'' And Dinkins called himself ``the guy that brings people
together.''
   The prime challenge for Dinkins, the Manhattan borough president,
is to bring even more voters together than he did in the primary. He
won nine in 10 black voters, half the Hispanics and roughly three in
10 whites, mainly the young and the liberal. But he lost Queens and
Staten Island, the boroughs with the largest white populations.
   ``The same people who said David couldn't win the primary for any
number of reasons _ too black, too Manhattan, too liberal _ now will
say the same thing about his race against Giuliani,'' Adler said.
   But broadening his appeal was Dinkins' byword in the primary. A
career officeholder who served 10 years as city clerk, he is a
formal, reserved and conciliatory figure, so reticent his critics
call him indecisive.
   ``Dinkins' principal asset is that he represents a new group
whose time has come,'' Moss said. ``He provides an opportunity for
blacks and Hispanics to take a major leadership role in municipal
government.''
   At the same time, he said, ``The challenge is for Dinkins to
disassociate himself from the perception that he's the candidate of
one interest group. And to demonstrate that he's a black candidate,
running for mayor, who is concerned with all people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
