<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-PilotTakeover Bjt   09-16 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilot Takeover, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Challenge For Pilots: Fly The Airline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dream of some pilots to buy their own
planes and run an airline is becoming reality for 6,326 United
Airlines flyers, who will have to learn to operate in the boardroom
as well as the cockpit.
   The federal government, Wall Street analysts, aviation experts
and employees of other airlines are watching closely the
employee-management buyout of United, approved last week by the
airline's parent company, UAL Inc.
   Some say it should make United's advertised ``friendly skies''
even friendlier, but the $7.2 billion deal that would make United
the nation's largest employee-owned company still faces some
obstacles and raises some scepticism.
   It won't be the first time a pilot has owned an airline or moved
in with management. But it will be the first time employees have
taken a controlling interest in a major carrier.
   The pilots' share would be 75 percent, with 10 percent held by
current management and 15 percent by British Airways PLC.
   The deal still faces potential hurdles, including participation
of the machinists and flight attendants unions and approval by
shareholders and the Department of Transportation. And despite UAL
approval, a competing bid by California billionaire Marvin Davis
still looms. On Friday, he offered to match the $300-per-share deal
if the pilot's plan falls through.
   ``Pilots spend more time in the cockpit discussing how they'd run
the airline than anything else,'' said Larry Crawford, a former Pan
American pilot who joined management and now runs AVITAS, an
aviation consulting firm.
   ``If anyone is cut out to run an airline, it's the pilots,'' he
said, but added that doesn't necessarily mean pilots will make the
best managers for a complex company like United. Some of them tend
to see little beyond the aircraft itself, he said.
   United pilots don't intend to actually run the airline, but they
will have a say in who does, and they expect some changes, including
less acrimony between employees and management.
   The plan calls for UAL Chairman Stephen Wolf and chief financial
officer John C. Pope to continue running the company for the new
employee-owners, said pilots spokesman Hank Krakowski.
   He predicted the deal will go through even without participation
of machinists, flight attendants or the company's 26,000 nonunion
employees. Negotiations are underway to include all 68,000 employees.
   Passengers might expect some changes, Krakowski said.
   Pilots are likely to announce over the plane's public address
system that the owner is at the wheel, he said.
   ``I think you'll see pilots more inclined to walk back into the
cabin and actually show an interest towards the customer,'' he said.
   Robert Joedicke, advisory director of the Wall Street firm of
Shearson Lehman Hutton, said United could become ``more attractive
from the aspect of service'' because employees who own the company
are more likely to project a friendly image.
   He said the deal also should make United more competitive on
fares because of the wage and work concessions.
   Aviation analyst Dean Stockman said the arrangement should not
make a difference in safety, because United already has a top
maintenance record, but he said it should make a more harmonious
company.
   ``They won't be arguing with management. They'll be arguing with
themselves,'' he said.
   Stockman said, however, the arrangement raises doubts about the
future of the Air Line Pilots Association, which represents pilots,
questioning whether pilot owners would want to stay in the powerful
union.
   ``Why should they pay dues to protect the employees from
themselves?'' he asked. ``We're in unchartered waters here.''
   Mark Daugherty, aviation analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds in New
York City, said the takeover could add to management problems.
   ``Management has a tough enough time. When you have different
voices and groups with different interests involved, it could be
even tougher to run the company,'' he said.
   But Daugherty added that ownership should give employees ``pretty
intense interest in making sure the company comes out OK.''
</TEXT>
