<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-Ivory     09-16 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-Ivory,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Confiscate 7 Tons of Ivory; Arrest Six</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WDH2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police confiscated 980 elephant tusks
weighing about seven tons Saturday and arrested six men suspected of
running an international ivory smuggling operation.
   Police said the haul was one of the world's largest seizures of
poached ivory.
   Police spokesman Kierie du Rand said the ivory would sell for
about $1.5 million. Police discovered it when they stopped a truck
at Okahandja, 45 miles north of Windhoek, he said.
   The tusks are believed to have come from elephants in southern
Angola and northern Namibia.
   Africa's elephant population has fallen from about 1.5 million in
1978 to as few as 400,000, due mostly to poachers who seek the
valuable tusks.
   Several Western nations, including the United States, recently
have banned the import of ivory, and the 102-nation Convention of
International Trade in Endangered Species will consider a worldwide
ban on the ivory trade next month.
   Angola's 14-year-old civil war has made it virtually impossible
to stop poaching in the southern part of the country.
   Namibia allows a limited legal trade in ivory.
   South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe hold similar positions,
saying properly managed ivory sales allow them to keep the elephant
population under control and generate revenue for conservation
programs.
</TEXT>
