<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PrecisionChoppers     09-16 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Precision Choppers,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0514 to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Team Wins Soviet Friends, Third International Crown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 16 members of the U.S. precision helicopter
team eagerly swapped war stories and tie tacks with their Soviet
competitors at the world helicopter championships, but struck out
when they tried to trade car license plates.
   ``Some guys had these great license plates made up for the team,
and wanted to trade, but none of the Soviets owned a car,'' recalled
pilot Jon Iseminger with a laugh.
   Iseminger and his co-pilot and navigator Rudolph V. Hobbs took
the top individual honors at the competition, held last week outside
Paris. Both Army warrant officers are helicopter instructors based
at Fort Rucker, Ala.
   As part of the seven-team U.S. contingent, they came away with
the United States' third consecutive championship, and a lesson in
the men they could possibly face off against should the superpowers
ever go to war.
   Hobbs, who admits to being dubbed ``Mushmouth'' by his comrades,
acknowledged that when words failed, hand signals often made do.
   But the business of flying wasn't topic No. 1.
   ``We exchanged war stories, and talked about our ways of life,''
Hobbs said in a telephone interview from Belgium after the
competition. ``They didn't speak English very well, but they
understood it better.''
   Iseminger, who also was the pilot of the winning crew at the last
world meet in 1986, said the Soviets ``were a lot more open, a lot
more jovial and friendly'' than during previous years, an apparent
reflection of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's new policy of
openess toward the West.
   However, the friendly communication had its limits.
   Although the military background of the U.S. team was clear _ it
was made up of four active Army teams and three Army National Guard
teams _ the Soviets refused to say whether they were currently in
the military or not, Iseminger said.
   The level of competence needed in the contest would not easily be
obtained in the Soviet Union without a military background.
   The international competition is open to civilians, and 38 crews
from six nations participated. The Soviets came in second, the
British third, French fourth and West Germans fifth.
   The competition is a grueling challenge that requires an immense
amount of concentration, and precision in navigation, flying and
timing.
   Competitors must fly through four events: a 150-kilometer
navigation course; a 80-kilometer course that must begin and end at
a specific time with a load dropped off during the exercise; a
precision flying event; and a slalom and skill course.
   For example, during the 80-kilometer test, a crew is handed a
packet five minutes before takeoff that contains exact takeoff and
arrival times and the course route. Contestants must take off on
time, arrive on time and then thread a glass bottle suspended on a
20-foot rope through a hole in a box, without breaking it.
   The Americans flew the OH-58 Kiowa scout helicopter, used
primarily to spot targets for other helicopter gunships on the
battlefield. The Soviets used the MI-2, or Hoplite, a utilitarian
transport or combat chopper.
   ``It takes skills, but it really boils down to mental toughness,
and who handles pressure best,'' said Iseminger.
   The pilot, who in his job checks on the capabilities of other
pilots, said the testing is useful for a military pilot.
   ``It's like money in the bank,'' he said. ``You may not need to
use these skills everyday, but you know inside yourself that you can
use them when you need them.''
   Hobbs, who tattled that his winning comrade was known as the
``ice man'' for his cool flying under pressure, said the Soviets
appeared to have inferior training, and that he wouldn't worry about
meeting such competitors in a war zone.
   ``I don't think so,'' Hobbs said. ``Really, there was just
something lacking. They just couldn't cut the mustard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
