<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     09-16 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nagasaki Nuclear Foes Protest U.S. Navy Port Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters in Nagasaki trampled on a wreath offered
by a U.S. Navy captain who was seeking Saturday to commemorate
victims of the atomic bombing of that city.
   About 50 chanting protesters, many survivors of the bombing,
refused to allow Capt. Peter Roberts of the U.S. frigate Rodney M.
Davis to approach a large memorial statue in the center of
Nagasaki's Peace Memorial Park.
   The statue is dedicated to victims of the U.S. atomic bombing of
Nagasaki at the end of World War II.
   Roberts and other crew members instead placed a wreath about 100
feet away from the statue. After they left, several protesters
pushed the wreath over and stamped on it.
   National television broadcast scenes of the protest.
   The Japan Broadcasting Corp. quoted Senji Yamaguchi, chairman of
the Nagasaki Atomic Bomb Victims Council, as saying the group was
protesting because of the possibility the ship was carrying nuclear
weapons.
   The agency quoted Roberts as saying he regretted the incident,
but that it would not affect his friendship with the people of
Nagasaki.
   Japan forbids the production, possession or introduction of
nuclear weapons into its territory, but many people believe U.S.
Navy ships routinely enter Japan with such weapons aboard.
   Kyodo News Service reported that Nagasaki Mayor Hiroshi Motoshima
refused to accompany Roberts to the park Saturday after Roberts
refused to confirm or deny that nuclear weapons were on board the
ship.
   The frigate is the first U.S. Navy ship to visit Nagasaki since
the city decided in 1974 not to allow port calls by ships from
countries that possess nuclear weapons, Kyodo said.
   It said the city agreed to the visit because of the mutual
security treaty between the United States and Japan.
   The U.S. military maintains a policy of not publicly confirming
or denying the presence of nuclear weapons.
   An estimated 70,000 people died when the United States dropped an
atomic bomb on Nagasaki on Aug. 9, 1945, three days after the city
of Hiroshima became the world's first victim of an atomic attack.
</TEXT>
