<FIRST>r w AM-IRAs-Savings 1stLd-Writethru a0507 09-16 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRAs-Savings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0507,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>For release 5:30 p.m. EDT, TIME set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS two grafs after 5th, The study ..., to give details.
^IRA Tax Breaks Help Savings Rate, Bentsen Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. savings rate fell sharply after
Congress slashed tax deductions for most individual retirement
accounts, according to a congressional study released Saturday by
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, has called for
restoring partial tax deductions on contributions to IRAs instead of
cutting the capital gains tax. He said the new study shows their
effectiveness in promoting savings.
   ``Now if we're going to be less dependent on foreign investment
and foreign loaning of money to us, then we have to increase the
savings rate in this country,'' said Bentsen.
   Bentsen said the study found that after 1986, when use of the IRA
was severely curtailed by cutting back on the tax deductions,
``savings rates dropped substantially in this country _ and they
were already low _ and that in addition the IRAs themselves were cut
almost in half.''
   The study, by an economist for the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress, found ``the weight of evidence suggests that IRAs generate
savings which otherwise would not occur, although the precise net
increase remains controversial.''
   The study said the personal savings rate averaged 5.3 percent of
disposable income from 1982-86 and has averaged 3.7 percent since
then. The rate fell to 3.2 percent in 1987-1988, the lowest in 40
years, according to the study.
   Savers contributed $38 billion to IRAs in 1986, but the amount
fell to almost half that the following year, the study said.
   The congressional study also mentions analyses by professors
Steven Venti of Dartmouth College and David Wise of Harvard
University, that suggest net national savings is increased by an
amount up to one-half the size of total IRA deposits.
   ``If true, then IRAs could play a productive role as a complement
to deficit reduction in efforts to boost U.S. savings, investment
and productivity,'' the congressional study said.
   Bentsen has proposed a deduction of at least 50 percent for all
IRA accounts. His plan would allow the withdrawal of IRA funds
without penalty at the time of retirement, for a down payment on the
purchase of a first home, or to finance college costs.
   ``That would help us bring interest rates down in his country,
that kind of an increased savings,'' said Bentsen. ``That would make
us much more competitive and slow down some of the consumer binge in
this country. It would help us with our trade deficit.''
   Bentsen argues his plan would have a much broader base of support
and would go farther in pulling interest rates down, and in
increasing productivity and investment, than a cut in capital gains.
   President Bush is pressing for a cut in taxes on profits from the
sale of stocks, real estate and other investments. The House Ways
and Means Committee, over the objections of the House Democratic
leadership, voted Thursday for the capital gains cut.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890916-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1309EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Budget     09-16 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Budget,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Prepares Emergency Plan to Slash Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government has prepared an emergency
1990 budget aimed at cutting the deficit in half within a year and
slashing capital spending to improve supplies of consumer goods.
   But the budget, to be introduced to the Supreme Soviet
legislature, already is coming under attack by at least one leading
reform-minded economist who says parts of it are too austere.
   Committees begin work Monday and the budget will be submitted to
the full legislature when it goes back to work a week later.
   The 1990 budget will seek to cut the deficit from $192 billion to
$96 billion, the Tass news agency reported Saturday.
   The plan calls for slashing spending on new factories and
production equipment by 30 percent while calling for an ambitious
6.7 percent increase in production of consumer goods, the Tass
report indicated.
   Some of the country's most radical economists say many economic
problems are based in the decades-old practice of setting high
production targets that are not feasible and ignore the quality of
the goods produced.
   Other legislation will call for the establishment of a Soviet
securities market, Tass said. But the report gave no details on that
or actual figures included in the budget.
   In a nationwide television speech Sept. 9, President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev said the government's program to work out of the deficit,
consumer shortages and other economic ills ``may include unpopular,
probably tough and even painful measures.''
   He said the government led by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzkhov would
have to come up with a practical plan to eliminate consumer
shortages that now encompass sugar, soap, meat, cigarettes and many
other basic items. Many cities are rationing such items in an effort
to halt hoarding.
   It was only a year ago that Soviet officials announced for the
first time the country had any kind of budget deficit, and the
Supreme Soviet passed a budget with a $58 billion deficit in a
budget of almost $800 billion.
   However, much of the deficit was hidden by accounting tricks, and
estimates of the 1989 budget deficit quickly mushroomed.
   One leading economist, Abel Aganbegyan, said in an article in the
September issue of the monthly Government Herald that the plan to
cut $153.8 billion in capital outlays by 30 percent is too severe.
   ``Speaking honestly the proposal ... frightens me,'' he wrote.
``I think this could lead to extremely negative consequences. You
can't go from one extreme to the other.''
   Soviet budgets for years have been burdened by huge outlays for
new factories, buildings and equipment at the expense of basic
consumer goods. Gorbachev and his economic advisers now say much of
the equipment and many of the buildings were unnecesary in the first
place, and are operating inefficiently if at all.
   But Aganbegyan, an adviser to Gorbachev, said the 1990 budget
plan goes too far in cutting those expenditures. The Ministry of Oil
and Gas Construction, for example, is planning to freeze millions of
rubles worth of construction equipment and thousands of miles of
pipeline and discharge 76,000 highly qualified workers, he wrote.
   The economist said the capital budget should be cut by about 20
percent, with $8 billion set aside to help Soviets finance private
housing construction.
   The other $24 billion should be used to increase public housing
construction, the number of private garden plots and family resorts,
and set up a program to help consumers buy highly sought-after items
such as cars, video equipment and personal computers, he said.
   The budget is likely to come under tough scrutiny by Supreme
Soviet committees, which under the new government structure
instituted this year have become much more critical of government
programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890916-0085 </DOCNO>
