<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0503 09-16 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 3rd graf from end, ``Brown said xxx to fix typo in Shevardnadze's
first name, deleting ``o''</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Policy Quandary: What to Do When Vietnamese Leave?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two weeks before Vietnamese troops are to
withdraw from Cambodia, the Bush administration is in a quandary
over what it should do to block the resurgence of the Khmer Rouge, a
group that murdered up to 2 million people in the 1970s, U.S. and
congressional officials say.
   ``Basically, what's happening is that most people are trying to
figure out what to do since Paris,'' said a senior administration
official, referring to the collapse of a 19-nation peace conference
in Paris last month.
   ``People are trying to absorb what went on,'' the official said,
speaking only on condition his name not be used. ``What do we do
when, and if, the Vietnamese complete withdrawal?''
   Participants at the Paris conference failed to come up with a
political solution for easing tension among warring factions in
Cambodia after the Vietnamese leave. Hanoi has said it will pull its
troops out by Sept. 30, ending a 10-year occupation.
   The vacuum has created the ``very real possibility that the
genocidal Khmer Rouge could battle its way back to power in Phnom
Penh,'' said Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the House
Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Asian and Pacific Affairs.
   Fred Brown, an expert on Indochina and former scholar at the
Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, a think tank, said the
administration is in a ``genuine dilemma'' about Cambodia. ``In the
wake of the Paris conference, there are serious questions'' about
U.S. policy, he said.
   A major concern are the ties between the Khmer Rouge and Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, the former Cambodian monarch the United States
supports with millions of dollars in aid. Washington would like to
see Sihanouk head an interim government pending free elections
supervised by the United Nations.
   Although members of Sihanouk's family were murdered by the Khmer
Rouge, which ruled Cambodia between 1975-1979, Sihanouk has endorsed
the idea of including the Khmer Rouge in a transitional government
in Cambodia.
   Both the Khmer Rouge and Sihanouk receive military aid from
China. Other factions in Cambodia are the Vietnamese-backed
government of Hun Sen, and a smaller non-communist faction.
   Some observers at the Paris conference said Sihanouk abdicated
too much of his authority to the Khmer Rouge. ``Is he every going to
loosen himself from the Khmer Rouge?'' Brown asked. ``Nobody can
come up with a leader to replace Sihanouk.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle, who is expected to discuss the
Cambodian situation with Asian allies on a trip to the Far East this
week, told a group of reporters last week that ``the non-communist
resistance has always been, from our viewpoint, the best hope to see
a political settlement occur in Cambodia.''
   Members of Congress echoed concern about Sihanouk.
   ``I think we ought to make clear to Sihanouk that either he and
the non-communists break all their ties to the Khmer Rouge, or they
don't get any help from us,'' said Rep. Chester Atkins, D-Mass.
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, suggested Pol Pot be brought before an
international tribunal on charges of genocide. He said the United
States should not go along with Sihanouk's apparent acquiescence on
the Khmer Rouge.
   ``The United States does not have the luxury of recusing itself''
on moral issues,'' he said.
   The Bush administration says its adamantly opposes a return to
power of the Khmer Rouge, an extreme nationalist group with about
40,000 fighters.
   ``We want to ensure that there are not more Cambodian killing
fields,'' said Richard Solomon, assistant secretary of state for
East Asian affairs.
   At the same time, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the administration has noted that Sihanouk as well as Washington's
Asian allies have ``said that the Khmer Rouge elements should
participate in the political process.''
   Atkins claimed administration officials used ``the most twisted
and distorted logic that I've ever seen in foreign policy'' in
defending a policy that opposes the Khmer Rouge while seeming to go
along with Sihanouk's idea of including it in the government.
   But Solomon said on Capitol Hill last week that it would be
``self-delusional'' to ignore the Khmer Rouge, a force to be
reckoned with in Cambodia.
   And one administration official explained the dilemma. Excluding
the Khmer Rouge means the rebels assuredly would launch a military
offensive to seize power, creating a ``little Lebanon in Southeast
Asia,'' he said.
   By bringing some Khmer Rouge ``under the tent, there's a
possibility that peace will break out,'' he said.
   As Solomon put it: ``The chances of avoiding conflict are not
very good,'' but they are better with a political settlement.
   Complicating the situation are the Soviets and the Chinese.
Solomon said the United States believes Moscow has stepped up arms
shipments to the Hun Sen regime in recent months. ``The Soviet
Union, as a primary supporter of Vietnam and Hun Sen, must restrict
its increasing flow of arms into Cambodia,'' he said.
   Brown said Secretary of State James Baker III is likely to broach
the issue in talks with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
later this month. The United States also wants China to end its arms
supplies to the Khmer Rouge.
   Meantime, the administration has asked Congress _ and received
approval _ to spend about $7.5 million in humanitarian aid for
Cambodia in fiscal 1990, up about $2.5 million from the previous
year.
   But sources on Capitol Hill said Bush administration have not
requested any covert assistance for military equipment in the
upcoming fiscal year. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
