<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Baltics     09-16 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Urges Compromise in Baltics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev urged the Baltic
republics to compromise with their minorities and settle the
region's ethnic disputes, Tass reported.
   The Soviet president spoke at a meeting with Communist Party and
government leaders from Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia. Tass released
its report on the Wednesday meeting late Friday.
   ``All our problems should be tackled by joint effort in the
framework of the federation,'' Gorbachev said.
   All the country's 15 republics are tied together economically,
culturally and through human contacts, he said.
   ``If we now allowed the situation to deteriorate to the point
where these ties would start to break up, the republics and the
whole country would be rolled back by decades,'' Gorbachev said.
   He added that ``any attempt to infringe on citizens' rights on
the ethnic basis should be regarded as contradicting the principles
of Soviet statehood and humanism.''
   Gorbachev's social reforms, including greater tolerance of
dissent, has fueled a wave of nationalism in the Baltics and other
Soviet republics.
   The Baltics are seeking greater autonomy and freedom from Kremlin
control. But the growing nationalism also has heightened tensions
among ethnic Russians and other minority groups who live and work in
those republics, and who claim they are targets of discrimination by
the ethnic majority.
   Non-Estonian workers in that republic struck last month after the
Estonian government passed rough residency requirements for voting
and running for local office.
   Gorbachev's conciliatory tone comes after the Communist Party
Central Committee last month warned that separatists were leading
the Baltic republics into an abyss.
   Estonian radio editor Harry Tiido said Friday that in interviews
given when he returned to Tallinn, Estonian Communist Party chief
Vaino Vyalyas said Gorbachev spoke favorably about the republics'
plans for more economic autonomy.
   More than a million Baltic residents joined hands on Aug. 23 to
protest the 50th anniversary of a Nazi-Soviet agreement that paved
the way for Moscow to annex the Baltic states.
</TEXT>
