<DOCNO> AP890916-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArabLeague-Lebanon     09-16 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab League-Lebanon,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Calls for Cease-fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab League committee called
Saturday for an ``immediate and comprehensive'' cease-fire in
Lebanon, but admitted it has no power to enforce the appeal.
   ``The Lebanese crisis will not be resolved by military means,''
Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal read from the
declaration of the Tripartite Supreme Arab Committee comprising
Saudi Arabia's King Fahd, Moroccan King Hassan II and Algerian
President Chadli Bendjedid.
   It said the cease-fire is necessary ``to stop the bloodshed and
establish an atmosphere conducive to assuring the return of
security, stability and national reconciliation.''
   The call followed a night of savage shelling duels in Beirut that
killed 12 people and wounded 72 others. Saud could offer no
guarantee for the success of this latest in a string of cease-fire
efforts by the 22-member Arab League.
   ``The committee possesses no weapons with which it would impose
its will in Lebanon,'' Saud said.
   But he said Syria, whose troops are battling the Christians in
Lebanon, supports the new peace plan.
   The declaration called on all parties to stop supplying weapons
to the combatants and said the committee already has received
``positive responses in this regard.''
   Iraq has been arming the Christians. Syria backs Lebanon's
Moslems, who want a bigger share of power in the country
traditionally dominated by the minority Christians.
   A ``Lebanese Security Committee'' to be headed by Algerian
diplomat Lakhdar will implement and oversee the cease-fire,
monitoring all ships reported to be carrying weapons or ammunition,
Saud said.
   As soon as the security body begins its work, naval blockades
would be lifted and Beirut International Airport reopened, the
declaration said.
   Ibrahimi is expected in Beirut on Sunday and also is to negotiate
the location of a Sept. 30 meeting of the Lebanese parliament ``to
discuss and prepare the National Reconciliation Charter.''
   The Arab League has blamed the failure of previous peace efforts
mainly on Syria's refusal to withdraw its 40,000 troops from
Lebanon. Damascus wants to link such a pullout to the withdrawal of
Israeli troops in southern Lebanon.
   ``In the final analysis all foreign non-Lebanese forces will have
to leave Lebanon,'' said Saud.
</TEXT>
