<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica 2ndLd-Writethru   09-16 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0529,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Stand Back as Blacks Bury Slain Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 20th pvs, ``He has ...'' to UPDATE with
minister named to talk to blacks; picks up 21st, pvs, ``In another ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CPN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists pledged to expand their
anti-apartheid campaign Saturday as they buried victims of election
night violence in black and mixed-race townships outside Cape Town.
   Police were present at the four funerals Saturday, but kept a low
profile as part of a new government policy not to disrupt peaceful
demonstrations and gatherings.
   ``Death will not deter those struggling for a free South
Africa,'' the Rev. Lionel Louw told about 4,000 mourners at St.
Augustine's Anglican Church in the mixed-race township of Grassy
Park.
   ``Do you see the blood of our martyrs? Can you hear them speak?
These are atrocities committed against our people. We can't allow
(police) brutality and call it law and order any longer,'' Louw said
at the service for Pedro Page.
   Page, 18, was one of at least 23 people of black and mixed-race
that activists say were killed the night of Sept. 6 in violence
instigated by police.
   Police gradually have raised their figures in recent days and now
say there were 10 deaths in black-on-black faction fighting and nine
killings in which police may have been responsible.
   The mourners traveled two miles from the church to the cemetery,
guided by young activists serving as volunteer traffic marshals.
   The only visible police were traffic officers, and some gave
their bright orange vests to the marshals and watched from afar.
   Asked how he felt about the marshals taking over his job, one
mixed-race policeman said, ``I think it's wonderful.''
   In the past, police have placed tight restrictions on the
funerals of activists and prohibited political speeches at the
ceremonies.
   Two funerals were held in the black township of Khayelitsha, and
prominent activist Rev. Allan Boesak led a funeral service for
13-year-old Patrick Muller in the mixed-race township of Bellville.
   Boesak said activists would resume marches on ``whites-only''
beaches beginning Sept. 30 and would extend major protest actions to
the southern cities of the eastern Cape Province. He called on the
government not to act against a huge anti-apartheid convention set
for Oct. 7 in Johannesburg.
   The Mass Democratic Movement, a loosely-based anti-apartheid
coalition, launched a nationwide campaign of defiance on Aug. 2. The
organized demonstrations aimed at segregated schools, hospitals,
beaches, buses and other facilities have been peaceful.
   However, spontaneous clashes have erupted repeatedly between
young activists and police, particularly in the townships
surrounding Cape Town.
   President-elect F.W. de Klerk, in a major policy shift, announced
Tuesday that the white-led government would not block peacful
protests, which previously had almost always been banned.
   More than 20,000 people joined a Cape Town march Wednesday
against police brutality, the largest such demonstration ever
authorized by the government.
   About 15,000 chanting protesters marched through the heart of
Johannesburg and 2,000 took over the central square of the capital,
Pretoria, on Friday.
   All the demonstrations have been peaceful and the only reported
police action has been against white hecklers.
   De Klerk, who will be sworn in for a five-year term Wednesday,
has portrayed himself as a reformer who wants to bring the 28
million black majority into the national government on a limited
basis within five years.
   He has said he wants to begin negotiations with black leaders on
a new constitution. But Boesak said conditions for such talks would
include lifting the 3-year-old state of emergency, releasing
political prisoners such as Nelson Mandela, and legalizing
organizations such as Mandela's African National Congress guerrilla
movement.
   De Klerk announced Saturday that Gerrit Viljoen, a former
minister of black education, will spearhead the negotiations for the
government. The Cambridge-educated Viljoen, 63, has a reputation as
a bookish, soft-spoken, political moderate close to de Klerk.
   In another development, Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok will
meet early this week with 40 mixed-race policemen, including Lt.
Gregory Rockman.
   Rockman has become a folk hero among township youths since he
began accusing police riot units of causing violence by beating
protesters, bystanders and shoppers during anti-election
demonstrations.
   ``(Police) are going to tag me as a terrorist and a Communist,''
Rockman, 30, said Friday at a memorial service for one of the
victims of the election violence, 13-year-old Leonard Ras.
   But, he added, other policemen ``have the same ideas and views as
me and this is a sign of hope for us in South Africa. I know I am
not alone.''
</TEXT>
