<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WaterWoes     09-16 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Water Woes,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Restrictions Are Sign of Times as Dry Season Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida already is in its worst dry spell since the
1950s and its annual six-month dry spell is less than two weeks
away, meaning little relief can be expected before spring.
   With most of the state already under voluntary or mandatory
water-use restrictions, the outlook of water managers, farmers and
environmentalists has turned from caution to concern.
   ``We may go into the dry season with one of the lowest reservoir
storage levels in recent history,'' said Broward County Water
Resources Management Director Roy Reynolds.
   On Thursday, the South Florida Water Management District board
declared a water emergency and urged voluntary water cutbacks by
almost 4 million people in Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties.
   Lake Okeechobee, a principal source of drinking water for
residents of southern Florida, is about 3 feet below its normal
level for this time of year.
   To boost the lake's level, the water board decided to pump farm
water runoff into it. That runoff normally would flow south through
the Everglades.
   Environmentalists attacked the so-called ``back-pumping,'' saying
the phosphorus-rich runoff promotes algae growth that robs marine
life of oxygen.
   The restrictions, which may become mandatory next month, include
limiting car washing and lawn watering to three times a week between
4 a.m. and 8 a.m., said Tilford Creel, the deputy director of the
district, which covers 16 counties from south of Orlando to the Keys.
   During the 12-month-old drought, responsible for extensive brush
fires in the Everglades last year that occasionally shrouded Miami
in smoke, rainfall has been below normal in all sections of the
state, except the Panhandle.
   ``This is the all-time low in what we have for total surface
water storage,'' said Creel.
   In the 16-county Southwest Florida Water Management District,
which includes St. Petersburg and Tampa, mandatory water
restrictions have been in effect since February.
   The tough measures have generated some spirited vigilantism.
   In Bonita Springs, for example, the local newspaper has printed
the names and addresses of residents ticketed for water violations.
   Penalties for violating the mandatory restrictions in the
Palatka-based St. Johns River district could go as high as $500 and
60 days in jail, although most people receive only a warning for a
first violation, said spokesman Ed Albanesi.
   ``People just assumed the water was going to be there. But
attitude is slowly beginning to turn around,'' he said.
</TEXT>
