<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   09-16 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0546,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Soldiers Wounded in Border Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Israeli officials meeting
to discuss Egyptian peace plan; picks up 3rd pvs, `The border...;' Deletes
last graf pvs to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assailant opened fire Saturday on an Israeli
army patrol from the Jordanian side of the border, slightly injuring
two soldiers in the third such attack this month.
   In the occupied territories, clashes between Palestinian youths
and Israeli soldiers reportedly injured four Arabs, and a
Palestinian man shot in a clash with troops last week died of his
injuries.
   Leaders of Israel's two main parties met Saturday to discuss a
Middle East peace plan offered by Egypt. Two meetings last week
failed to bridge differences over the plan, which calls for
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
   The border incident occurred in pre-dawn darkness near the
communal settlement of Ashdot Yakov, three miles south of the Sea of
Galilee.
   Israel radio said the assailant apparently was a Jordanian army
soldier who ran to the border and ambushed the Israeli patrol,
firing about 30 rounds while hiding behind a bush. The Israelis
returned fire.
   A Jordanian army spokesman told Jordan's official news agency,
Petra, that a Jordanian soldier fired at an ``unusual movement''
along the Jordan River and that ``Israeli patrol cars ... fired in
the same direction and that resulted in a slight injury to one of
our people.''
   Another Jordanian official told The Associated Press the
firefight appeared to be ``an accident.''
   ``It was night, and when you are on the cease-fire line, (you
know) how alert you are to any unusual movement,'' he said.
   The Israeli soldiers suffered slight shrapnel wounds.
   It was the sixth attack this year on Israel from along the
Jordan-Israel border and the third this month. The most recent
attack occurred Sept. 7, when several Soviet-designed Katyusha
rockets were fired from Jordan into Israel. There were no injuries.
   In the occupied territories, Palestinians paralyzed the West Bank
city of Nablus with a general strike to protest the deaths Friday of
two Palestinian youths shot by Israeli troops.
   Another Palestinian, 45-year-old Samir al Akhbar, died Saturday
of wounds suffered in a clash with troops last week, officials at
Anglican Hospital in Nablus said.
   Arab reports said Akhbar was shot in the back while trying to
keep soldiers from beating his son.
   Israeli officials said he was shot when he tried to grab a
soldier's gun.
   His death raised to 571 the number of Palestinians killed in
clashes with Israelis in the 21-month-old uprising against Israeli
rule of the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Forty Israelis have died, and
114 Arabs accused of collaborating with Israel have been killed by
other Arabs.
   Arab reporters said four Palestinians were wounded in clashes
Saturday. The army said it was checking the reports.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak proposed a 10-point peace plan
that includes Palestinian elections in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and Israeli-Palestinian peace talks in Cairo that would include two
Arabs deported from the occupied lands.
   That aspect of the plan is designed to satisfy Israel's demand to
talk only to Palestinians from the territories and the PLO's
insistence that Palestinians living abroad be included in talks.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc and the
left-leaning Labor Party led by Finance Minister Shimon Peres are
deeply divided over the plan.
   Labor leaders have indicated their willingness to talk to a
delegation including deported Arabs, but Likud officials view it as
an attempt to bring in the Palestine Liberation Organization through
the back door.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
