<FIRST>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru   09-16 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0500,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Appears For First Time in Three Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to fix typo in 2nd graf; picks up 3rd pvs:
He displayed ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping appeared in public
Saturday for the first time in more than three months, looking tan
and healthy despite recent reports he was seriously ill or even near
death.
   National television news showed the 85-year-old leader laughing,
gesturing animatedly and walking steadily at the start of a
70-minute meeting at the Great Hall of the People with T.D. Lee, a
Nobel Prize-winning physicist from Columbia University.
   He displayed his bronzed hand to Lee, and said he had been
swimming for up to an hour a day in the sea. ``I don't like indoor
swimming pools,'' he was heard to say, ``but enjoy swimming in
nature.''
   Deng reportedly spent part of the past three months, among the
most traumatic in Communist China's history, at Beidaihe, a favorite
resort for top officials along the northeast coast.
   Deng, China's most powerful leader, has cut down on his public
duties in recent years and has often disappeared for long periods,
each time sparking rumors he is seriously ill.
   But this time both Chinese and foreign sources consistently
reported that he was being treated for prostate cancer and may not
have long to live. The lively Hong Kong press in recent weeks
reported Deng to be in a coma or already dead.
   Deng's last public appearance was on June 9, when he
congratulated martial law officers for their leadership in quelling
what he called a ``counter-revolutionary rebellion'' intent on
overthrowing the Communist Party and the government.
   Troops stormed Beijing June 3 and June 4, killing hundreds and
perhaps thousands of people as they shot their way to
student-occupied Tiananmen Square.
   Deng also is believed to have had the ultimate say in the
decision, announced June 24, to purge Communist Party General
Secretary Zhao Ziyang and accuse him of splitting the party by
supporting the pro-democracy goals of the student protesters.
   Zhao, the top advocate of economic reforms initiated by Deng 10
years ago, has not been seen in public since May 19. He is believed
to be under house arrest while the party decides whether to press
criminal charges against him.
   Deng, in an apparent reference to Zhao, said Saturday that ``some
of our comrades just immersed themselves in their specific work, did
not pay enough attention to ideological and political developments,
were not vigilant enough against the serious corruption.''
   ``The recent turmoil has taught us a major lesson,'' Deng said.
``After the turmoil, all of us have become sober-minded.''
   Deng, whose support of economic reforms has generally been
tempered by a hard line against political dissent, said China will
not change its policies of reform.
   But he added that China must stick to socialism. ``There would be
no new China today without the leadership of the Communist Party,''
he said.
   Deng also echoed the conservative line on reform by saying
production must develop at ``an appropriate pace,'' rather than the
rapid pace preferred by Zhao that is now being blamed for inflation
and corruption.
   Deng's comments, as carried by television news and the official
Xinhua News Agency, did not specifically mention Zhao.
   In 1987, Deng retired from all his official posts except the
powerful chairmanship of the Central Military Commission. However,
he is still regarded as the only man powerful enough to maintain a
truce among the party's different factions, and rumors of his death
invariably raise fears of a destabilizing power struggle.
   In recent days, Chinese officials have suggested Deng was about
to emerge in public, possibly to reassure the Chinese people before
Oct. 1 _ the 40th anniversary of the People's Republic _ that the
government leadership is intact.
   Lee, a Chinese-American who won the Nobel Prize for physics in
1957 and is a frequent visitor to China, was not available for
comment on his meeting with Deng or a luncheon afterwards.
   Lee also met later with Zhao's successor as party chief, Jiang
Zemin, who spoke of current efforts to help students ``enhance their
political awareness and make a clear distinction between right and
wrong.'' Those efforts include heavy doses of political education.
   Xinhua said Jiang also told Lee that Chinese leaders have shown
``much concern'' for civilians injured or killed during the military
takeover of the city.
   China says about 300 people were killed during the clashes, but
Chinese leaders have made no public statements of remorse for the
bloodshed and the official media have not reported on civilians who
lost their lives.
</TEXT>
