<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--TankerAdrift     09-16 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Tanker Adrift,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Tanker Drifts For an Hour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An empty Exxon oil tanker lost power and drifted
about an hour in the Strait of Juan de Fuca before regaining some
maneuverability and heading for Port Angeles, the Coast Guard said.
   The 810-foot Exxon San Francisco lost power about 8:30 p.m.
Friday as it was 33 miles west of Port Angeles and five miles north
of Slip Point, near the west end of the strait, said Petty Officer
Sandy Calhoun in Seattle.
   Three Coast Guard cutters and a helicopter responded from Port
Angeles, but the ship had regained about 40 percent of its
maneuverability by the time they arrived, Ms. Calhoun said.
   The Coast Guard vessels escorted the ship to Port Angeles.
   The cause of the problem was not immediately released.
   Last March, the Exxon Valdez struck a reef in Alaska's Prince
William Sound and spilled about 11 million gallons of oil in the
nation's worst oil spill.
   The Strait of Juan de Fuca connects Puget Sound and the Pacific
Ocean. Tankers, many carrying Alaska crude oil, travel the strait
regularly to and from refineries near the Sound.
</TEXT>
