<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     09-16 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks and Whites Pay Tribute To Slain Guerrilla Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people packed a church in a
black suburb Saturday to pay tribute to Anton Lubowski, a leader in
the Namibian nationalist movement who was assassinated outside his
home.
   ``In a racially divided country such as ours, Comrade Anton's
role as a bridge builder will be sorely missed,'' said Theo-Ben
Gurirab, foreign affairs chief of the South-West Africa People's
Organization.
   Lubowski, 37, was shot in the head with an AK-47 assault rifle
outside his Windhoek home Tuesday night. Police are holding
50-year-old Irishman Donald Acheson in connection with the killing,
but no one has been charged.
   Lubowski was the only ranking white member of the Namibian
nationalist guerrilla movement against South African rule.
   The Lutheran Church in the Katutura neighborhood was overflowing,
and about 200 people listened from outside the church doors to the
service for the man to be buried this week.
   Lubowski's parents, his ex-wife and two children were there,
along with several diplomats such as Robin Renwick, Britain's
ambassador to South Africa. ``Nothing can justify so callous a
murder of a man ... who devoted the best part of his time to
fighting for a truly non-racial Namibia,'' Gurirab said. ``Did it
really have to happen now, at a time when his country and people
needed him most?''
   Namibia, which has been ruled by South Africa since 1915, is
having elections in November expected to lead to independence early
next year.
   South Africa agreed to implement independence under U.N.
supervision after signing a regional peace treaty last year that
also calls for the withdrawal of Cuba's 50,000 soldiers from Angola.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, which waged a
23-year bush war for black majority rule, is favored to win the most
votes.
   Lubowski, a prominent human rights lawyer, in 1984 became the
first white to publicly declare his support for the guerrilla-backed
organization. He joined its legal political wing and served as the
group's unofficial spokesman in Windhoek while most of the
leadership was in exile.
   Right-wing newspapers often ridiculed Lubowski for belonging to
the leftist-oriented organization.
   Lubowski studied at two of South Africa's best universities,
Stellenbosch and Cape Town, and at one point was an officer in the
South African army.
   His law practice was based in Windhoek, but he represented many
anti-apartheid activists on trial in neighboring South Africa.
   Lubowski helped represent 14 blacks sentenced to death for the
mob killing of a black policeman in 1985. Four days before
Lubowski's death, the 14 won an appeal to have their case retried.
</TEXT>
