<DOCNO> AP890916-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Kissinger     09-16 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kissinger,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Defends China Business</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger said
Saturday his private business dealings in China do not represents a
conflict with his statements as a former public official.
   Kissinger's comment on CNN's ``Newsmaker Saturday'' came in
reaction to an article Friday in The Wall Street Journal dealing
with his business interests in China.
   ``I was involved in the opening of China,'' said Kissinger. ``I
have a record of 20 years of writing and speaking on China. For four
years after I left government I did not do any commercial
activities. For six years I did not do any consulting activities.
   Kissinger said national government service and ``serving my
country has been my principal objective and to assume that any
commercial consideration could affect the judgments that I expressed
publicly is an outrage and it is a form of intimidation by which
people who disagree with me are trying to keep me from expressing my
views.''
   The Journal reported Kissinger has extensive business interests
in China, including the establishment of a $75 million fund to be
raised from U.S. investors for joint ventures with the merchant
banking arm of the Chinese government.
   In addition, his consulting firm, Kissinger Associates, counsels
several businesses on how to conduct operations overseas and,
specifically, in their dealings with China, the Journal reported.
   A spokeswoman for ABC News said Friday that the network would not
have used Kissinger as a paid expert on a China special last June
had it known of his business ties there.
