<FIRST>r a AM-Brites SUB   09-16 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, SUB,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS first item in brites package to drop extraneous words from
lead and second graf and fix spelling of McDonald's in second graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pizza Hut is jumping into the fray in the
pizzas wars, urging diners not to make a ``Mcstake'' and try the
pizza McDonald's is offering at a few outlets. The upshot? An
outwardly mild-mannered war of words, half of them prefaced by
``mc.''
   The burger giant professes itself pleased with the Pizza Hut's
advertising counter-campaign, even though it goes so far as to
compare McDonald's pizza to a hockey puck.
   ``We want to thank them for giving our own ad campaign some extra
topping,'' said McDonald's spokesman Chuck Rubner, who said he was
``Mcdelighted'' with the attention.
   Pizza Hut launched the campaign in newspapers and on television
after McDonald's added pizza to the menu at 24 outlets in southern
Indiana and western Kentucky this summer. The burger colossus hopes
to lure families and couples during the dinner hour, a slack time
for much of the fast-food business.
   ``If you're looking for great pizza, make no Mcstake,'' Pizza Hut
fires back in some of its ads. ``We always use dough that's made
fresh daily. Not McFrozen.''
   A television ad shows hockey players taking slap shots at a
puck-shaped blob of frozen dough.
   Although Pizza Hut has about 22 percent of the $314
billion-a-year pizza market, it's not taking the McDonald's test
lightly.
   ``The television commercial is very humorous,'' said Roger
Rydell, a spokesman for Pizza Hut in Wichita, Kan. ``We're being,
however, very serious to our approach to the McDonald's threat.''
</TEXT>
