<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-16 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain and Storms Affecting Wide Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A hurricane neared the Caribbean and a tropical depression spread
rain over the Southwest on Saturday, and rain fell across the
Midwest and much of the East.
   Hurricane Hugo headed for the Leeward Islands and hurricane
warnings were posted for Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
Its highest sustained wind speed was about 140 mph, with stronger
gusts.
   Tropical depression Octave spread moist air over the Southwest.
Light rain caused slippery streets in the Los Angeles basin and fell
from San Diego to Santa Barbara. Thunderstorms over the Diablo
Mountains and Livermore Valley dropped about half an inch of rain
near Livermore, Calif.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over western Arizona.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended over southern Lower
Michigan, Indiana, northern Ohio, Kentucky, West Virginia, western
New York state, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Virginia, Maryland, North
Carolina, eastern South Carolina, the Georgia coast and the Florida
coast.
   A tornado was reported on the ground in North Carolina's Lenoir
County on Saturday afternoon.
   Almost 4 inches of rain fell at Fayetteville, N.C., in two hours
late Friday and more rain fell overnight, causing flooding in which
two children drowned.
   In parts of West Virginia, creeks were swollen by more than 3
inches of rain Saturday, forcing some families to leave their homes
and drowning two people, authorities said.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over western Washington state.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53 at
Bremerton and Everett, Wash., to 100 at Phoenix. Saturday's low for
the Lower 48 states was 19 at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Sunday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from New
England and New York state across eastern South Carolina, eastern
Georgia and the Florida Peninsula, as well as from the Pacific Coast
across Montana, western Wyoming, Utah and Nevada.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted over New England and New
Jersey across the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and the Appalachians,
from Montana, Idaho, western Utah and northern Arizona across the
northern two-thirds of the Pacific Coast, and along the southern
coast of California; near 90 over much of Florida, much of Texas,
western Oklahoma and western sections of the central Plains; in the
90s over North Dakota and western South Dakota, as well as from
southern Arizona through the desert Southwest; and generally in the
80s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
