<FIRST>r w AM-Jackson-CapitalGains     09-16 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Capital Gains,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Forces to Visit Districts of Congressman Who Voted For Capital
Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting a0583 to change dateline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said Saturday that his
Rainbow Coalition will go the districts of six Democratic
congressmen who voted to cut the capital gains tax, to alert their
constituents to the benefits the rich will gain.
   ``There is no justification for further subsidizing the rich
through the capital gains tax by abandoning the poor,'' said
Jackson. ``The capital gains tax is unfair. It is immoral. It must
be challenged.''
   On Thursday, the House Ways and Means Committee approved the tax
cut in an amendment to a larger tax bill. The reduction, sought by
President Bush, would lower the maximum tax rate on profits from
sales of assets from the current 33 percent to 19.6 percent for 2{
years.
   The rate then would be raised to 28 percent but assets would be
indexed to eliminate taxes based on increased value created by
inflation.
   The six, including Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., who co-sponsored the
amendment, joined with 13 Republicans to pass the proposal.
   But in so doing, the six Democrats incurred the wrath of
Democratic leadership.
   Jackson's action was supported at a news conference which was
attended by Democratic National Committee Chairman Ron Brown and
Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., a Ways and Means member.
   Brown called the tax ``unethical, immoral and it doesn't make
political sense'' for the Democratic party to ``give a tax break to
the wealthiest in our country'' at a time when the poor continue to
suffer.
   ``I think this is clear this is the worst example of Robin Hood
in reverse,'' Brown said.
   Former President Reagan attempted his version of trickle down
economics, Jackson said, in the belief the rich would help America
by reinvesting tax savings.
   ``They did not do that'' and the rich today probably won't
either, Jackson said. ``This is a payoff for the very elite of the
Bush campaign. It's not good for America.''
   Thus, Jackson said, the campaign was targeted at the ``six
Democrats who jumped ship and abandoned the party.''
   ``I'm concerned that these congressmen who broke rank'' have not
informed their constituents of their actions, and the poor and ``the
farmers are not aware of this,'' Jackson said.
   Besides Jenkins, the Democrats include Reps. J.J. Pickle of
Texas, Mike Andrews of Texas, Beryl Anthony of Arkansas, Andy Jacobs
of Indiana and Ronnie Flippo of Alabama.
   Rangel said his party was in a fight for its principles and that
the Democratic-controlled Congress had helped pass Republican
legislation the congressman said was bad for Americans and bad for
the party's principles.
   ``Certainly no six monkeys on the Ways and Means committee are
going to direct where my party is going,'' Rangel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
