<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Arafat     09-16 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Arafat,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Session Opens Tuesday, No Decision Announced on Arafat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly opens its 44th session
Tuesday in New York still uncertain if PLO chief Yasser Arafat will
again seek to address the delegates.
   U.S. officials said the leader of the Palestine Liberation
Organization has not made a request for a visa. They declined to say
if one would be granted if Arafat did submit an application.
   Arafat was denied an entry visa last year to attend a U.N.
session in New York because U.S. officials said the PLO was backing
anti-Israeli terrorism. Instead, the international body convened a
meeting in Geneva where Arafat outlined his ideas about the PLO's
mission and its attitude toward Israel.
   At this year's General Assembly session the delegations of 159
nations will review such issues as the Middle East, the environment,
international debt, the war on drugs, and Namibia's transition to
independence.
   President Bush will address the assembly Sept. 25, the first day
of the three-week general debate. Soviet Foreign Minister Edouard
Shevardnadze is scheduled to appear the next day.
   Colombia's President Virgilio Barco Vargas will speak Sept. 29
about his nation's battle against its cocaine cartels.
   PLO officials have said Arafat is ``seriously considering''
attending the session. The Palestinian conflict is scheduled to be
discussed in November, but Arafat could address the assembly during
the general debate.
   Last year then-Secretary of State George Shultz denied Arafat a
visa, but since then the United States has opened direct talks with
the PLO in Tunisia.
   U.S. officials said last week the United States won't announce
whether it will grant a visa to Arafat until a new request is
received.
   U.S. and Arab sources said privately that the State Department is
divided over whether to grant such a request and Secretary of State
James Baker has not yet ruled on the issue.
   The Assembly is expected to choose a new president Tuesday,
replacing Argentina's Dante M. Caputo.
   Under a system of rotating regional representation the African
nations will nominate the candidate for president this year. They
have proposed Nigeria's U.N. ambassador, Maj. Gen. Joseph Garba.
   The first main session of the General Assembly ends in
mid-December, but the body will then hold a five-day special session
on the apartheid system of racial segregation in South Africa.
   The assembly session is expected to formally close in September
1990.
</TEXT>
