<FIRST>r a AM-MassCitizenship     09-16 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mass Citizenship,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>4,000 Hispanics Become U.S. Citizens in Festive Holiday Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 4,000 Hispanics were sworn in as U.S.
citizens Saturday in an emotional ceremony timed to coincide with
local celebrations of Mexico's Independence Day.
   ``It was very emotional. It just gets you back in touch with our
liberties and what it means to be a U.S. citizen,'' said Lupe Ramos,
an organizer of the citizenship ceremony.
   Organizers billed the Weingart Stadium event as one of the
largest of its kind for a particular ethnic group.
   U.S. District Judge Manuel Real administered the oath of
citizenship and tiny flags were distributed to each of the 3,950 new
citizens, representing 19 Latin American nations.
   Mexican nationals, at 2,546, accounted for the majority of those
sworn in Saturday. Others included 333 Salvadorans, 229 Cubans and
182 Guatemalans, Ms. Ramos said.
   ``You can imagine how beautiful it is when you have 4,000 people
waving the flag and screaming because this is what they've been
waiting for,'' she said.
   After the ceremony, many registered to vote at booths set up by
local political activists.
   Among the new citizens were a family of eight from Mexico who
originally worked in the United States as field hands, and Raul
Lavista and his son, Raul Jr., both of whom served in the U.S. Navy,
Ms. Ramos said.
   The ceremony coincided with the 179th anniversary of the start of
Mexico's independence struggle, celebrated with the 48th annual
Mexican Independence Day parade in East Los Angeles.
   Father Miguel Hidalgo's call to arms sparked the first Mexican
uprising against Spanish rulers in 1810. The rebel priest was
captured and killed the following year, but his action eventually
led to independence from Spain in 1821.
</TEXT>
