<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Election     09-16 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Election,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Non-Communist Wins Hungarian By-election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in a southeastern district
elected an opposition legislator to Parliament Saturday, handing the
Communists their fourth straight defeat in special elections,
according to preliminary results.
   The by-elections have demonstrated strong anti-Communist
sentiment ahead of general elections scheduled to be held by June.
   Also Saturday, reform Communists preparing for a showdown with
hard-line party members established an organization calling for
peaceful change. They elected the most liberal member of the
country's four-man leadership, Imre Pozsgay, to head the Movement
for a Democratic Hungary.
   Citing preliminary results from Saturday's polling, state
television reported that 59 percent of the voters chose opposition
candidate Gyula Marx in Zala county on the Yugoslav border.
   Marx was supported by the Hungarian Democratic Forum, the League
of Young Democrats and the League of Free Democrats.
   He defeated Communist candidate Istvan Gyoerffy and Istvan
Schein, an opposition Social Democrat.
   The newscast reported a turnout of 61 percent of eligible voters,
but it gave no other details.
   Three other opposition legislators won by-elections in July and
August, shutting out Communist candidates in the first multi-party
voting since the Communists consolidated power in Hungary in 1947.
   The Communist leadership decided in February to endorse
multi-party elections, arousing suspicions among some of its East
bloc allies. The general elections to fill more than 300 Parliament
seats are to be held by June.
   Pozsgay, speaking after he was elected to head the Movement for a
Democratic Hungary, said the organization was open to people of most
political persuasions, but not Marxists resisting the change to a
multi-party democracy.
   Reformers are preparing for a fight with party hard-liners at a
Communist congress set for Oct. 6.
</TEXT>
