<FIRST>r i AM-Algeria-Government     09-16 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Algeria-Government,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Names New Government With Reformer Majority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Mouloud Hamrouche on Saturday
appointed mainly Western-oriented technocrats and people viewed as
reformers to a new Cabinet.
   Hamrouche, named to the job a week ago by President Chadli
Bendjedid, picked Sid Ahmed Ghozali, former head of the state oil
and gas monopoly Sonatrach, as foreign minister.
   Bendjedid's announcement on Sept. 9 that Premier Kasdi Merbah had
been fired for opposing a reform program briefly led to a
constitutional crisis, as Merbah tried to retain his post. But he
gave way later the same day.
   The nomination of Ghozali as foreign minister was the most
significant of Hamrouche's new appontments. Ghozali, 52, is a main
partisan of Bendjedid's reform program, which includes introducing a
multiparty political system and increasing the role of private
enterprise in the state-directed economy.
   He headed Sonatrach for 12 years, building it into a massive
state enterprise.
   Later, Ghozali became minister of hydraulics in what was widely
regarded as a demotion. He then was named Algerian ambassador to
Brussels. He returned to the government as finance minister in 1988.
   Ghozali is considered a Western-oriented technocrat advocating
economic and financial reform.
   His appointment was a signal that Bendjedid is determined to push
ahead despite obstacles from the Old Guard of the ruling party. The
National Liberation Front has held power since Algeria won
independence from France in 1962.
   Other ministers considered enlightened technocrats were Ghazi
Hidouchi, economics minister; Hacene Kahlouche, minister of heavy
industry; Smail Goumeziane, minister of commerce; Hamid Sidi Said,
minister of posts and telecommunications. They have long worked
closely with Hamrouche, formerly the government's secretary-general.
   In the new Cabinet, the Ministries of Information, Culture,
Tourism and Veterans Affairs were abolished, in another move seen as
signaling transformation of an autocratically ruled state into
something closer to a Western-style democracy.
   The Ministry of Information, headed by a succession of party
stalwarts, was widely criticized for maintaining rigid controls over
the Algerian press and radio introduced by the late president Houari
Boumedienne.
   After October's riots in Algiers and other cities, Bendjedid
promised to free the press, radio and television from state control.
He also announced his program of political pluralism.
   Hamrouche's Cabinet keeps just three ministers from the previous
government in their same jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
