<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Glemp 1stLd-Writethru a0584 09-16 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Glemp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0584,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glemp Calls for Mutual Understanding on Convent Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 5 grafs after 7th pvs, On Friday... to include more quotes.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's Roman Catholic primate, Jozef
Glemp, has called for mutual understanding to resolve conflict over
a convent next to the Auschwitz concentration camp.
   In an interview published in the Catholic weekly Tygodnik
Powszechny, Glemp said it might be possible to renegotiate
agreements to relocate the convent farther from the former Nazi
death camp.
   The Carmelite convent is at the center of a controversy between
some Catholics and Jews over an agreement reached in 1987 under
which Catholic negotiators agreed to move the convent to a nearby
interfaith prayer center by Feb. 22.
   Glemp continues to back the convent, which was established in
1984 in a building the Nazis used to store gas to kill Jews and
other death-canp inmates. He has said the agreement, signed in
Geneva, was not negotiated by ``competent people''
   In the interview published Friday Glemp said Jews should help
Catholics become better acquainted with Jewish views on the issue.
   ``Let mutual understanding be the common intention,'' he said.
   On Friday, Glemp met with the head of a fund that restores Jewish
monuments in Poland to discuss a possible resolution to the
international controversy, the state news agency, PAP, reported. No
details were provided but PAP said ``a draft of a satisfying
solution of the Auschwitz conflict was shaped.''
   Zygmunt Nissenbaum, with whom Glemp met, maintains a family
philanthropic fund. The proposals worked out by the two ``will be
carried further by an appropriate group that will handle concrete
realization'' of building the interfaith center, PAP said.
   In the interview, Glemp spoke of his earlier remarks that were
considered anti-Semitic by some Jewish leaders.
   ``Some of the press reactions (to the sermon) made me realize
that several of my opinions were interpreted contrary to my
intentions,'' he said. ``I thought the whole of my enunciation on
the need for friendly dialogue between Catholics and Jews is
sufficently clear.''
   Some Jewish groups and others consider the convent to be an
intrusion of Christian symbols at the former concentration camp
where 2.5 million of the estimated 4 million people killed were Jews.
   At one point during the interview the interviewer said it is
``better to move it (the convent) 1@3 of a mile away in tune with
the Geneva settlements. It is no tragedy and the Lord will hear
their prayer from a new place as well.'' Glemp replied, ``Of
course.''
</TEXT>
