<FIRST>u a AM-PrintShopMassacre 1stLd-Writethru a0540 09-16 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Print Shop Massacre, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0706</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funerals Begin For Victims Of Print Shop Carnage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to RECAST lead; include that reporters barred
from funerals and UPDATE with second funeral held. Picks up 11th graf,
`Funerals for...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK R. CHELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funerals were held Saturday for victims of
Thursday's massacre at a printing plant, with a chorus singing,
``Nearer My God To Thee,'' for a slain choir member.
   The Thoroughbred Chorus performed at the funeral for James Wible,
a long-time chorus member who was among the shooting victims at
Standard Gravure Corp. where he worked for 37 years.
   Wible's funeral was the first held for the seven victims of
Joseph T. Wesbecker, a deranged co-worker who entered the building
spraying bullets from an arsenal he had been collecting during the
past few months.
   Eleven of the 13 people injured by Wesbecker during the rampage
remained hospitalized Saturday, two of them in critical condition.
   Wesbecker, who turned a pistol on himself to end the shooting
spree, did not have a formal funeral. Bill Longest, an official at
Owen Funeral Home in Louisville said Saturday that the body was
embalmed and taken away. Longest said Wesbecker's family asked that
no other information be divulged.
   Reporters were barred from Saturday's services.
   Dan Burgess, a chorus member who attended Wible's funeral, said
the Rev. Gene Templar made only a few references to the violence
that caused Wible's death. Burgess said Templar's eulogy stressed
that ``God's will is about love and not about violence.''
   Chorus members also sang ``The Lord's Prayer'' and ``I Thank the
Lord.''
   Wible was to be buried in Illinois.
   Funeral services were also held Saturday for Richard O. Barger,
54, a pressman for 32 years; and a service was scheduled for
Saturday evening for Sharon L.L. Needy, 49, a receptionist at the
downtown plant, which prints newspaper inserts.
   Funerals for the other four victims were scheduled for Monday.
   Among those attending Wible's funeral was Michael Shea, the owner
of Standard Gravure. Shea, who appeared very upset, did not say
anything after the ceremony, but consoled Wible's family members and
friends.
   Meanwhile, Wesbecker's son James Thomas Wesbecker blamed Standard
Gravure for the mental problems that his father suffered.
   ``Maybe this was just his way of ending it,'' the younger
Wesbecker said in an interview Friday with the Lexington
Herald-Leader. ``I don't want to say much about the company, about
the people at the top. Maybe they didn't know what was really going
on. I'm not sure.
   ``But I feel like, over the years, the company created my dad,''
he continued. James Wesbecker, 22, is one of Wesbecker's two grown
sons by his first marriage.
   Wesbecker was on long-term disability from the company because of
his mental problems. Relatives have told police he was a manic
depressive who had attempted suicide three times.
   James Wesbecker said his father feared the company was planning
to take away some of his benefits. ``He was really afraid of that,''
the younger Wesbecker said.
   Shea said Friday that he knew of no meeting company officials had
planned with Wesbecker and refused to comment on what he called
``the speculaton, rumors and innuendo'' about Wesbecker's
relationship with the company, where he went to work in 1971.
   Meanwhile, the shooting began a debate in Kentucky over
regulations on assault weapons of the type Wesbecker used. When he
entered the printing plant, Wesbecker was armed with a Chinese-made
AK-47 semiautomatic rifle, two MAC-11 semiautomatic weapons, a
revolver and a 9mm semiautomatic pistol.
   Two Louisville legislators said they will introduce a bill in the
1990 General Assembly to ban the sale of AK-47 rifles and similar
assault weapons. Kentucky lawmakers are in general so strongly
against gun controls that there is a state law that bars cities and
towns from passing gun control ordinances.
   State Rep. Mike Ward acknowledged that passage of a gun-control
law would be difficult. ``But I think we owe it to the families of
the victims, and the surviving victims, to try to make it at least
harder to obtain assault weapons,'' Ward said.
</TEXT>
