<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Ibarruri     09-16 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Ibarruri,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spanish Communist Leader Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leader Dolores Ibarruri, known as
``La Pasionaria'' for her fiery speeches during the Spanish Civil
War, was in serious condition Saturday with pneumonia, her doctors
said.
   The 93-year-old party stalwart was taken to Madrid's Ramon y
Cajal hospital early Thursday with breathing problems.
   In a statement Saturday her doctors said her condition had not
improved despite treatment with antibiotics.
   However, a report in the newspaper El Pais said Mrs. Ibarruri
managed to sit up in a chair Friday and chat with relatives.
   Mrs. Ibarruri was one of the Spanish Communist Party's founders
in 1920. She is now its honorary president.
   She became famous as a Parliament member during the 1936-39 civil
war for her radio broadcasts exhorting Republican forces to defeat
Gen. Francisco Franco's troops.
   During the 1937 siege of Madrid, her defiant phrase _ ``They
shall not pass!'' _ became the battle cry of loyalist Republican
forces.
   After Franco's victory she went into exile in the Soviet Union.
   She returned to live in the Spanish capital in 1977 as Spain
carried out a peaceful transition to democracy following Franco's
death two years earlier.
   That same year the white-haired grandmother won back her deputy's
seat in the lower house of Parliament. She later gave it up because
of her age and health.
</TEXT>
