<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Europe-USTrade     09-16 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-US Trade,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Trade Representative `More Positive' About European Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills
said Saturday she was in a ``more positive frame of mind'' after a
week of discussing American complaints about European trade policies.
   ``I think we can work out of this,'' Mrs. Hills told a news
conference after meeting with top officials of the European Economic
Community, the 12-nation trading bloc known as the Common Market.
   Neither side, however, reported solving any of their trade
disputes, such as a European ban on imports of hormone-treated beef
or American steel-import quotas. The European Community last year
was the United States' largest trading partner.
   During her trip Mrs. Hills expressed concern that some of the
Common Market's policies might hurt American companies.
   But Frans Andriessen, the chief trade official for the European
Commission, the bloc's executive body, said the community intends to
remain open once it forms a single market in late 1992.
   There has been concern in the United States about proposals that
appear to place protectionist barriers around the European-wide
market in 1992, when trade barriers restricting the free movement of
money, goods, services and people will be removed.
   But after talks in five other European cities, Mrs. Hills said,
``I am of a more positive frame of mind today than I was (last)
Saturday when I arrived in Paris.''
   Mrs. Hills was scheduled to return to London Saturday before
going on to Rome on Sunday and returning to the United States on
Monday.
</TEXT>
