<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     09-16 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Found After Abduction Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYFIELD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who police said was abducted and
drugged then found five days later wandering a Florida beach was
among six people killed when the plane carrying them to her ``quiet
homecoming'' crashed and burned.
   Belinda Yancey, 33, and five other people, including her husband,
died Friday night when the airplane's wing struck a tree and went
down near the Mayfield-Graves County airport in southwestern
Kentucky, authorities said.
   ``As far as people going through one tragedy and then all getting
killed, I've never seen anything like that before,'' said Kentucky
State Police Lt. Tom Finck, who was at the crash site Saturday.
   Ms. Yancey, who taught hearing impaired students at Mayfield High
School, disappeared sometime after 2:30 p.m. Monday, when she told
her son that she was going to Murray State University's bookstore,
said police Capt. Bob Crawford. Her car has not been found.
   She wandered up to a lifeguard on a beach at Daytona Beach, Fla.,
on Thursday afternoon and said she was lost, police said.
   Based on statements she made to Florida authorities, Ms. Yancey
seemed to have been drugged with Valium by her abductor, who
remained at large, Crawford said.
   Ms. Yancey told authorities that ``they kept giving me little
blue pills,'' Crawford said.
   In interviews with authorities and relatives, she could not
recall how she got to Florida and was unable to identify who drove
her there, Crawford said.
   Ms. Yancey's hair had been cut and dyed and she had bruises on
her arms, indicating she was tied up or restrained, he said.
   After the disappearance, she was disoriented and didn't know her
name, said Sgt. Carroll Rountree of the Volusia County, Fla.,
Rangers. Mrs. Yancey finally remembered her name and hometown after
talking to Rountree for about two hours, he said.
   The Rev. Alfred Cobb, a family friend, said only Mrs. Yancey's
closest family members knew about her scheduled return from Florida
on Friday night.
   ``They tried not to tell too many people, because they didn't
want a big crowd at the airport,'' Cobb said. ``They thought, in
fact I think they were told, that it would be better for Belinda's
health if there wasn't a lot of people there because of the
situation she was in.
   ``No one else was aware of (the group) being on their way home.
They were looking for a quiet homecoming.''
   Finck said the twin-engine Beechcraft BE-10 was flying through
thick fog as it approached the airport. The pilot made two attempts
to land before the crash, but apparently lost sight of the runway
both times, Finck said.
</TEXT>
