<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia 3rdLd-Writethru   09-16 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0590,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Bombs Explode; Security Increased</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with two bombings, Pickup 3rd,
`Colombia celebrated...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs, one thrown from a motorcycle
and a second from a car, exploded in downtown Bogota Saturday as the
government tightened security to quell the wave of violence.
   Two pedestrians were injured when the devices exploded at about 5
p.m. in front of two banks, which were closed, a police spokeswoman
said.
   The banks, Banco de Santander and Banco Popular, are in the
Paloquemao area of central Bogota.
   No one claimed responsibility for the bombings but it is believed
they were connected to the drug-related violence that began four
weeks ago when the government announced its crackdown on drug
traffickers.
   Meanwhile, hundreds of soldiers patrolled city streets and
searched cars for weapons and explosives. Police said nine people
were killed and 15 wounded in widespread violence Friday.
   Colombia celebrated its ``Day of Love and Friendship'' _ the
equivalent of Valentine's Day. But shopping centers, usually filled
with people buying last minute gifts for the holiday, were nearly
deserted.
   Americans continued to pull out of Colombia for fear they could
be caught up in the month-long war between drug traffickers and the
Colombian government.
   About 20 American passengers boarding flights Saturday for the
United States told a reporter they feared for their lives. In the
last two weeks, outgoing flights have been filled with Americans.
   Two weeks ago, the U.S. Embassy ordered dependents of American
employees out of the country.
   A bomb was deactivated at the Colgate-Palmolive Co.'s
headquarters in the western Colombia city of Cali Thursday night,
police Col. Rozo Julio Navarro told The Associated Press.
   Three bombs exploded Friday night in Cali, injuring 13 people,
Navarro said. The bombs went off in a high-rise building and damaged
three banks and 12 stores, he said. No one claimed responsibility
but police suspected the drug cartels.
   On Saturday the army, declaring a maximum alert, put troops and
armor into the streets of Colombian cities in the greatest display
of military muscle seen in years here.
   Troops were patrolling Bogota, the cocaine cartel centers of
Medellin and Cali, and the Caribbean coastal cities of Cartagena and
Barranquilla.
   Early in the morning, hundreds of troops in trucks poured out of
the army's 13th Brigade headquarters in northern Bogota. Foot
patrols were seen throughout the capital of 6 million.
   Soldiers searched people, mostly men, in downtown Bogota, and the
army and police set up checkpoints to search vehicles for guns and
explosives.
   For the first time, Colombia's national police acknowledged
numerous telephoned threats to people in Bogota and said the
telephone company is setting up an operation to trace such calls.
   Troops also were deployed to guard banks and government buildings.
   Banks are frequent targets of the nation's powerful cocaine
traffickers, who have declared ``total and absolute war'' on the
government. That declaration and the Aug. 18 assassination of
leading presidential candidate Sen. Luis Carlos Galan prompted the
crackdown on drug lords.
   At Bogota's El Dorado International Airport, police closed off
all but two entrances and were frisking people and searching bags.
   Police Col. Nassin Yanine Diaz, commander of the Bogota division
of the national police, appealed in a communique Saturday for people
to remain calm and ``have confidence in the armed forces.''
   A similar communique was issued by the 13th Brigade.
   Two policemen were killed by gunfire from a speeding car Friday
night in Bogota, said a spokesman for national police headquarters
in the capital.
   As in most bombings and shootings throughout this country of 30
million, police said they had no idea who was behind the violence.
Drug traffickers have been widely blamed but leftist guerrillas
seeking to topple the government have waged their own campaign of
violence.
   In the central Colombia state of Boyaca, just north of the
capital, seven men were killed Friday in violence involving bandits
battling for control of Colombia's emerald mines, the national
police in Bogota said.
   Drug traffickers are believed to be heavily involved in the
20-year-old struggle for control of the emerald mines.
   Also in Bogota, a gunman firing from a car shot at the building
of the Bogota daily El Siglo Friday night, the Bogota police said.
   An El Siglo executive said one shot was fired in the air by a man
who became angry when he was stopped by guards checking vehicles
entering the El Siglo parking area.
   The man and a passenger fled in the car, the El Siglo spokesman
said, asking not to be identified. No one was reported injured.
   A bomb seriously damaged the Bogota daily El Espectador on Sept.
2. The paper's publisher, Guillermo Cano, was assassinated by drug
traffickers three years ago.
   In Medellin, a bomb exploded near a police vehicle Friday night,
injuring two policemen, police said in a telephone interview.
   Thirty-two bombs have exploded in Medellin Since Aug. 21.
   Last week the army said it had arrested 28 persons in Medellin on
suspicion of being leftist guerrillas and of setting off some of the
bombs that have exploded there.
</TEXT>
