<FIRST>r a AM-DestroyerLaunched     09-16 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Destroyer Launched,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Destroyer Launched; Salvos Fly at Dingell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATH, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Navy's new $1.2 billion destroyer
Arleigh Burke was launched Saturday, officials took turns firing
return salvos at a congressman who called the ship's construction a
``procurement nightmare.''
   ``Irresponsible attitudes like that hurt but ... don't take them
too seriously,'' Rep. Joseph E. Brennan, D-Maine, told a crowd
estimated at more than 10,000 people who attended the launching at
Bath Iron Works.
   The Burke is named for an 87-year-old retired admiral and World
War II hero who arrived at the launching in a 1930 Packard. Burke's
wife, Roberta, broke a bottle of champagne over the bow, sending the
8,500-ton destroyer sliding toward the Kennebec River.
   Construction of the ship, considered the most technologically
advanced surface combat vessel, has prompted complaints of cost
overruns by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich.
   Dingell, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee
on oversight and investigations, told the Navy that the program is
18 months behind schedule and that the DDG-51 destroyer is only 38
percent complete.
   ``The acquisition of the DDG-51 has turned into a procurement
nightmare,'' his letter said.
   Bath Iron Works rejected Dingell's assertions, which were based
on a draft report from the General Accounting Office, which is
conducting an inquiry into the program.
   Dingell's ``numbers are wrong, his facts are wrong and his
so-called news in nearly two years old,'' said Brennan. ``That
number of errors in not good even for congressional work.''
   William E. Haggett, chairman and chief executive officer of Bath
Iron Works, said Thursday that the DDG-51 is ''47 to 51 percent
complete, a higher level than we launched our previous prototype
ship.''
   ``The ship is ready in every respect to be launched,'' said
Haggett.
   Gov. John R. McKernan, who declared Saturday Arleigh Burke Day in
Maine, said, ``I don't care what Dingell says. This is a great day
for Bath Iron Works and a great day for the state of Maine and a
great for the United States of America.''
   The guided-missile destroyer is designed with a steel
superstructure instead of one that is part aluminum and more prone
to splintering and fire damage. It will be equipped with
sophisticated Aegis computers and Tomahawk cruise missiles.
   Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III said the ship ``represents
the very future of surface warfare.'' The ship is scheduled to be
delivered in February 1991.
</TEXT>
