<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     09-16 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Official Visits Haiti One Year After Coup</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A high-ranking U.S. State Department
official left Haiti on Saturday after a visit to assess progress in
democratization a year after Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril came to power in
a soldiers' coup.
   ``This visit reflects our deep interest in Haitian affairs,''
Bernard Aronson, under-secretary of state for Latin American and
Caribbean affairs, said before leaving.
   During his 24-hour visit, Aronson met with Avril, who came to
power on Sept. 17, 1988.
   ``We had the opportunity to talk directly, to view the progress
made, and to talk about future steps,'' said Aronson. He did not
elaborate.
   However, U.S. officials have recently praised Avril, saying he
has improved Haiti's human rights record and its efforts to combat
drug trafficking.
   Soldiers angered by what they viewed as state-sponsored violence
ousted former ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy a year ago and sent him
into exile in the Dominican Republic, which shares the Caribbean
island of Hispaniola with Haiti.
   The soldiers demanded respect for human rights and a return to
democratic rule.
   Avril was expected to make a speech on state television Sunday to
commemorate his first year in power.
   The general has promised to turn over power to an elected
government and allowed the creation of an Electoral Council. That
body is expected to announce later this month a timetable for
general elections.
</TEXT>
