<FIRST>r a AM-SunkenTreasure 1stLd-Writethru a0566 09-16 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sunken Treasure, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0566,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists At Site Of Sunken Gold Ship May Have Found Biological
Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with creatures brought ashore and
identified as invertebrate animals, picks up 4th graf, `The Central ...;
SUBS 9th graf pvs, `Both grow..., with 2 grafs to add detail; picks up
10th graf, ``It may...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explorers recovering gold that may value
more than $400 million from a sunken ship off the South Carolina
coast said Saturday they also may have found two previously unknown
species of marine life.
   Researchers using remote-control equipment gathered samples of
the two organisms, apparently invertebrate animals, attached to
remnants of the SS Central America at a depth of 8,000 feet, said
Barry Schatz, a director of the Columbus-America Discovery Group.
   The creatures will be studied on board and later taken ashore for
further study, said Schatz, who spoke with The Associated Press in a
ship-to-shore telephone conversation from the Arctic Discoverer
research vessel 200 miles offshore.
   The Central America sank during a hurricane Sept. 12, 1857, en
route from Panama to New York. It was carrying a monthly shipment of
gold from the San Francisco Mint to New York banks by way of the
Panamanian isthmus. The sinking claimed 425 lives; 153 people
survived.
   Remnants of the wood and iron ship, discovered three years ago,
lie on a section of ocean floor that Schatz said is a ``biological
oasis'' in the midst of an otherwise barren area.
   Charles Herdendorf, an oceanographer from Ohio State University
who heads an onboard research team, said scientists have been trying
to informally catalogue marine life seen around the wreck through
television cameras.
   ``But these two were just total mysteries to me,'' he said in a
ship-to-shore conversation. ``These looked really new.''
   Conversations with specialists at the Smithsonian Institution in
Washington heightened belief that the creatures were previously
unknown, Herdendorf said.
   Both appear to be invertebrate animals similar to sponge or
coral. They grow on stalks about eight to 10 inches long and may be
part of the same family, he said.
   One consists of a narrow stalk that ends in plumes or polyps. The
other has a coin-sized, fleshy growth extending off a central stalk.
   ``It may be the same organism in various life stages or it may be
two different species,'' he said.
   The group planned to spend Saturday on scientific research,
Schatz and Herdendorf said.
   In addition to collecting the two organisms, Schatz said, the
group hopes also to catch other animals with traps baited with
lobster from the group's dinner, scrape animals from the wreck hull
and take a core sample of the sea floor.
   Though the first of the gold was found in August 1988, the Arctic
Discoverer and its 21-member crew did not find the main gold deposit
until Aug. 27 this year, after about a month at sea.
   Schatz said the team may be at sea for another month, and hopes
to have the bulk of the gold up by then.
   As an offshoot of the commercial enterprise of recovering the
gold, the group established an adjunct sciences program, headed by
Herdendorf.
   More than a dozen researchers are now involved in the project,
including scientists from the Smithsonian.
   ``The economic payoff is what pays for the science,'' Schatz said.
   Herdendorf said the group hopes to produce educational films and
distribute their findings throughout the scientific community.
   ``It's really a dream. I guess the dream of all biologist is to
find new life forms and advance the horizons of science. We're
probably just beginning,'' Herdendorf said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
