<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 2200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Soviet     09-16 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Party Daily Says Soviets Repressed Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Saturday said
the Soviet invasion of Poland in 1939 led to repression and crimes
against millions of Poles.
   The paper, Trybuna Ludu, said the truth about the invasion must
be told before Polish-Soviet relations can be put on a new basis.
   ``The date of Sept. 17 is deeply rooted in the consciousness of
the Polish nation. Especially because the entering of Soviet troops
was followed by growing repressions, and even mass crimes, which
involved millions of Poles,'' the paper said.
   On Sunday, Poland marks the 50th anniversary of the Soviet
invasion, which came more than two weeks after the Nazi army entered
Poland at the outbreak of World War II.
   Germany and the Soviet Union had agreed to divide Poland into
spheres of influence under secret protocols in the
Ribbentrop-Molotov non-aggression pact on Aug. 23 of that year.
   Soviet troops are thought to have killed tens of thousands of
Poles during the war. Another 1.5 million were deported to Siberia
during the Soviet occupation.
   ``The crossing by the Red Army into the eastern borders of Poland
... belonged for decades in our country to the most taboo
subjects,'' the paper said. ``If Sept. 1 was the beginning of a
cataclysm for Poland and later for the world, then Sept. 17 that
year symbolizes a secondary blow that fell on our nation and the
consequences of which were also enormous and tragic.''
   Although Nazi aggression has been well publicized, the Soviet
invasion was rarely mentioned in the official press for decades. It
was, however, well documented in the unofficial or underground press.
   ``The truth about those events is deserved not only by the
victims of the repressions, their descendents, the whole nation, but
it is one of the important tasks in freeing Polish-Soviet
relations,'' Trybuna Ludu said.
   Ceremonies were planned Sunday at the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier
in Warsaw, and there will be other smaller commemorations nationwide.
   Two years ago, a joint Polish-Soviet commission was set up to
investigate ``blank spots'' in history such as the massacre of
Polish officers at Katyn, the Soviet invasion of Poland, and the
1920 Polish-Soviet war.
   Last Aug. 23, deputies in the lower house of parliament passed a
resolution condemning the Molotov-Ribbentrop pact as ``shameful.''
Earlier, the Communist Party had condemned the secret protocols as
``a flagrant violation'' of international law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
