<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 2243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Quake     09-16 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Quake,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>5.2 Quake Rattles Mexico; No Damage Or Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake measuring 5.2 on the Richter
scale shook southern and central Mexico on Saturday, but there were
no reports of damage or injuries.
   The National Seismological Service said the quake, which occurred
in the early evening, was centered 250 miles southeast of Mexico
City on the coast of Oaxaca state. The earthquake could be felt in
the Mexico City.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an earthquake
as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every
increase of one whole number means a tenfold increase in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 5 is defined as one that can cause considerable
damage.
   At least 10,000 people died and large areas of Mexico City were
leveled on Sept. 19, 1985, when an earthquake measuring 8.1 on the
Richter scale struck and a second temblor measuring 7.6 hit the next
day.
</TEXT>
