<FIRST>u a AM-BarneyFrank 1stLd-Writethru a0534 09-16 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barney Frank, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0534,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Says He May Not Run Again If Probe Hurts His Causes.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th, `Frank's disclosure...' to UPDATE
with Boston Globe editorial urging Frank to resign. Picks up 7th graf pvs,
`In the...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressman Barney Frank says he would consider not
running again if a House ethics probe of his relations with a male
prostitute damages the causes he considers important in Congress.
   ``Do other people who share my values pay a price if I am here?''
said the Massachusetts Democrat. ``If that's so, then I would not
run for office.''
   Frank conceded in an interview with The Boston Globe _ conducted
in Washington and published Saturday _ that disclosures about his
relationship with Stephen L. Gobie have already diminished his
influence on some of the liberal causes he has supported.
   A Newsweek poll released Saturday showed 46 percent of Americans
said Frank shouldn't be re-elected because of the scandal.
Forty-five percent said they would vote against any homosexual
candidate for office, according to the poll of 600 adults
interviewed Sept. 14 and 15.
   The same poll found 60 percent of Americans believe that being a
homosexual shouldn't keep a person from being a member of Congress
and 50 percent said homosexuality shouldn't keep a person from being
president. The poll has a 4 percent margin of error.
   Frank's disclosure of his homosexuality in 1987 didn't prevent
him for gaining 70 percent of the votes in his 1988 re-election bid.
He represents a predominantly Democratic district that encompasses
parts of southeastern Massachusetts and some Boston suburbs.
   The Boston Globe, in an editorial in Sunday's editions, urged
Frank to resign for ``his own good, and for the good of his
constituents, his causes and Congress.''
   The Globe noted that it had ``enthusiastically endorsed Frank
throughout his public career,'' but said revelations about Frank and
his relationship with Gobie had led it to conclude ``Barney Frank
must go.''
   ``The issue of Frank's conduct is not homosexuality but
prostitution, which is illegal and which has always been a
destructive element in heterosexual and homosexual life,'' the
newspaper said. ``Had the issue been heterosexual prostitution,
feminist groups would not have been silent. So far, Frank has
enjoyed more than the benefit of the doubt, he has enjoyed a double
standard.''
   In the interview, Frank said that if he retired, he would
practice law and do some writing, but would continue to be involved
in such issues as housing, AIDS and homosexual rights.
   Frank said he believes most people will agree with his contention
that his activities with Gobie involved only his personal life and
did not spill over into his work as a member of Congress.
   ``My impact on people who don't know me has been diminished
some,'' Frank said. ``As public spokesman, there will be a period
that I will have to reestablish.''
   Frank said he has decided to step back from the issue of the
scandal in the Department of Housing and Urban Development, on which
he has worked recently.
   ``On that one, I think it is appropriate that I pull back until I
get my own ethics matter resolved,'' he said.
   The House Committee on Standards of Official Conduct has begun a
preliminary inquiry that is expected to take up to three months.
   The study centers on Frank's hiring of Gobie, whom he once
patronized for paid sex, as his aide and chauffeur, allowing Gobie
access to his apartment; Frank's writing of several letters on
official stationery to Gobie's Virginia probation officer; and
Gobie's contention that Frank fixed up to 100 parking tickets for
him.
</TEXT>
