<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 2246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RiverSpill     09-16 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-River Spill,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fuel Spill Closes Part Of Hudson River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-mile stretch of the Hudson River was
closed to water traffic Saturday after several thousand gallons of
oil was discovered spilled in the river, authorities said.
   The river was closed from the Port of Albany to below Catskill
after a petroleum product believed to be a heavy fuel oil spilled
into the river late Friday night, according to officials from the
state Department of Environmental Conservation.
   The actual spill _ which originated in the Port of Albany _ was
about 20 miles long and extended from Albany to Coxsackie, said
Coast Guard officials from Governors Island in New York City.
   The spill was reported early Saturday, said R.W. Groneman, a
department spokesman. He said it wasn't known who made the call.
   ``The type and amount of the oil as well as the source are
unknown,'' said Petty Officer Jeff Crawley.
   Groneman said the spill was toward the western shore of the
river. He said there was concern over wildlife and waterfowl in the
area.
   ``The parties responsible for this hit and run environmental
disaster will face stiff penalties,'' said Commissioner Thomas
Jorling of the environmental conservation department. ``They will
also get a bill from New York state for the cost of the cleanup.''
</TEXT>
