<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LostMoney     09-16 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lost Money,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Turns in Lost $2,000 That Survived Rain, Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who found $2,000 in rain-soaked $100
bills strewn across a road gave the cash to authorities. The couple
who reported the money missing couldn't believe their good fortune.
   ``You're kidding me,'' was Jeanette Yakel's response, said
Lincoln County Sheriff's Chief Deputy Tom Casady. She said it twice.
   The money, lost on Aug. 23, survived up to 13 inches of rain over
a four-day period. The couple from Memphis, 30 miles outside
Lincoln, didn't know how they lost the money.
   ``We had flooding all over the place,'' Sgt. Robert Marker said.
``It's one of those once-in-a-lifetime deals you hear about.''
   William H. Landon, 35, of Greenwood, found the 20 $100 bills and
turned them over to the sheriff's office on Thursday. A check found
with the money helped verify the correct owners.
