<FIRST>r a AM-MineAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0595 09-16 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven of 10 Victims Killed in Mine Accident Buried</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT spelling of miner's name to Furgerson,
sted Ferguson; no pickup. ^LaserPhoto XHND1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANFIELD, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven coal miners were buried Saturday,
and an investigation into the explosion that killed them and three
others was delayed again because of dangerous levels of methane gas,
authorities said.
   The methane gas was in the area where the explosion is believed
to have occurred, said Kathy Snyder of the U.S. Mine Safety and
Health Administration.
   Ms. Snyder said federal and state investigators conducting a
preliminary check of the mine Thursday found ``explosive levels'' of
methane.
   The MSHA then approved Pyro's plan for correcting the levels,
but, ``So far they have been unable to clear up the methane problem.
And they're still in the process of doing that,'' Ms. Snyder said.
   ``Until that happens, the investigation will be on hold,'' she
said. ``The methane levels are too dangerous.''
   She did not know how long that would take.
   On Friday, Willard Stanley, commissioner of the state Department
of Mines and Minerals, said a blowtorch found near the site of the
explosion was most likely what ignited the blast.
   The Pyro mine has been cited for 1,508 violations and assessed
$215,757 in fines over the past seven years, according to MSHA.
About $53,000 was assessed this year.
   Funeral services began in the morning in Madisonville and
continued throughout the day in western Kentucky. One funeral was
held in Morganfield, two in Madisonville, another in Muhlenberg
County, and others in Nortonville and Salem.
   Mark S. Hedges, 31, of Morganfield, one of the 10 miners killed
Wednesday at Pyro Mining Co.'s William Station Mine in neighboring
Wheatcroft, was buried Friday. The other two victims were scheduled
for burial Sunday in Providence and Madisonville.
   In Madisonville, about 250 people packed a funeral home chapel,
two family rooms and the hallway for funeral services for Paul T.
Harris, 39, of Providence.
   The scene was repeated at the Whitsell Funeral Home in
Morganfield, where about 150 to 200 people paid tribute to Roger
Clifford, 32, of Morganfield.
   During the 15-minute service, the minister read a poem from an
Elkville, Ill., woman titled, ``Coal Miner's Wife.''
   Also buried Saturday were Lynn A. Ashmore, 31, and Kenneth E.
Reed, 32, both of Slaughters; Ernest W. Stewart, 40, of Mortons Gap;
James A. Tinsley, 36, of Marion; and Rickie Dale Furgerson, 34, of
Madisonville.
</TEXT>
