<FIRST>r a AM-Boise-Rally     09-16 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boise-Rally,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 11,000 Rally at Capitol in Opposition of Boise Cascade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 11,000 union supporters rallied
at the state Capitol to protest the hiring of non-union construction
workers at the Boise Cascade Corp. paper mill in International
Falls, the site of a riot last week.
   Also Saturday, a state lawmaker said he would introduce a bill to
repeal a $16 million tax exemption Boise Cascade is eligible to
receive from the state; and 200 to 300 people attended a peace rally
in International Falls to oppose violence in connection with the
labor dispute.
   The Sept. 9 riot at the International Falls plant caused more
than $1 million in damage at the $535 million expansion project and
resulted in five minor injuries and 29 arrests.
   No violence was reported in International Falls on Saturday,
police said, and the St. Paul and International Falls rallies were
peaceful.
   Several protesters carried signs praising Gov. Rudy Perpich for
supporting union labor and for not sending the National Guard to the
riot. Perpich has been criticized by Boise and the contractor for
the expansion for not deploying the Guard.
   More than 11,000 people attended the rally, according to Capt.
Richard Smith, director of Capitol security.
   Thousands of rallygoers, including many children, carried signs
protesting Boise Cascade and BE&amp;K, the contractor who hired the
non-union workers.
   A few said, ``Go home scabs,'' ``$16 million for education, not
rats,'' and ``My dad's union and I'm proud.''
   Anti-Boise Cascade buttons were being sold for $5 each, with the
proceeds to pay for legal help for the people arrested in the riot.
   In International Falls on the Canadian border, 200 to 300 people
gathered at Smokey Bear Park to show their opposition to violence in
connection with the labor dispute.
   ``We will not tolerate the violence that seeks to tear apart our
community,'' the Rev. Daniel Megorden told the crowd in Smokey Bear
Park, across from the Boise plant.
   ``None of us want to see neighbor torn against neighbor, brother
against brother,'' Megorden said.
   Most speakers at the hourlong rally in St. Paul, including
Minnesota AFL-CIO President Dan Gustafson and Minnesota Building
Trades Council President Bill Peterson, said they did not condone
the violence by pro-union activists last weekend.
   But they said the rioting occurred because Minnesota union
workers are frustrated over the hiring of non-union, out-of-state
workers at the expansion project, even as Boise became eligible to
receive the tax break.
   ``How has Boise used this tax credit?'' Peterson told the crowd.
``To hire BE&amp;K, a non-union contractor from Alabama, and to
subsidize the importation of non-union workers from 22 different
states who took jobs that rightfully belong to Minnesotans.
   State Rep. Joe Begich told rallygoers he would introduce a bill
to repeal the tax exemption during a planned special legislative
session on property tax issues this month.
</TEXT>
