<FIRST>u w AM-BlackCaucus 1stLd-writethru a0586 09-16 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Caucus, 1st Ld-writethru, a0586,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: To update, top 10 grafs new; picks up 5th graf previous, The
event</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Democratic mayoral nominee David
Dinkins won a thundering welcome Saturday night from black leaders
from around the country and told them, ``I promise you, I will not
let you down.''
   Dinkins, a black who defeated Mayor Ed Koch in the New York
primary five days ago, was met by a standing ovation as he appeared
before the annual awards dinner of the Congressional Black Caucus.
The dinner and fund-raiser attended by an estimated 4,000 people,
including elected blacks from around the nation.
   ``I recognize that I am a vehicle, an instrument,'' Dinkins said.
``I stand for a lot of folks whose philosophy is like mine.
   ``Everybody stands on somebody's shoulders,'' Dinkins said,
paying tribute to civil rights figure Rosa Parks and to the Rev.
Jesse Jackson, the two-time candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
   ``I promise you, I will not let you down,'' Dinkins said.
   Another black candidate seeking a ground-breaking victory,
Virginia Lt. Gov. Doug Wilder, who is the Democratic nominee for
governor and could become the first elected black governor, also
appeared briefly and received a standing ovation.
   The $300-per-plate dinner concluded the Congressional Black
Caucus' 19th Annual Legislative Weekend, a three-day gathering to
discuss social and legislative concerns of black Americans.
   Jackson, who spoke at earlier events, wandered through the large
banquet room at a Washington hotel sporting a Dinkins button in his
lapel.
   Members recalled and mourned the late Rep. Mickey Leland,
D-Texas, who died last month in a plane crash while visiting hunger
victims in Ethiopia. Leland was chairman of the House Select
Committee on Hunger. Instead of their customary musical
entertainment, caucus officials dedicated a portion of their program
to a remembrance of Leland.
   The caucus consists of 23 black members of Congress, all of whom
are Democrats and members of the House of Representatives. It was
first organized as a caucus by 13 black members in 1970. Since then,
blacks have increased in numbers and positions of seniority in the
Congress.
   The event was expected to raise more than $1 million from ticket
sales and corporate donations for the caucus's fund-raising arm, the
Congressional Black Caucus Foundation, according to its leaders.
   ``We should clear $1 million, and I think that's pretty good,''
said the senior black member of Congress, Rep. Augustus Hawkins,
D-Calif., who has served in the House since 1963.
   The event has also become a major social event for black
political leaders, attracting black stars from the sports and
entertainment worlds as well as black officeholders from around the
country. At one of the opening events, black television journalist
Kenneth Walker called the gathering ``African Americans' No. 1
party.''
   Johnnetta B. Coleman, president of the historically black Spelman
College in Atlanta, was to deliver the keynote dinner address on the
event's theme, ``A Global Crisis: Our Children At Risk.''
   Award recipients were:
   _ Georgetown University basketball Coach John Thompson, receiving
the George Collins Award for commmunity service.
   _ Hawkins, the William Dawson Award for legislative development
   _ Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., House majority whip, the Adam Clayton
Powell Award for political empowerment.
   _ Faye Wattleton, president of Planned Parenthood Federation of
America, the Humanitarian Award.
   _ Ron Brown, Democratic National Chairman, the Harold Washington
award for excellence in coalition building.
</TEXT>
