<FIRST>r a AM-LouieLouie     09-16 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louie Louie,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Asks That `Louie, Louie' Not Be Played at Stadium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of South Carolina told
opponents' marching bands not to play the song ``Louie, Louie'' at
its football stadium out of concern the structure could be damaged
by dancing fans.
   South Carolina's marching band last played the song at the
Nebraska game in 1986. Fans in the east upper deck of the
Williams-Brice Stadium caused the stadium to sway, and those below
the deck became alarmed.
   Engineering studies performed after the Nebraska game showed the
stadium to be safe.
   ``Structurally, if you've got the whole student body out there
jumping up and down constantly for 75 years, you might have some
metal fatigue,'' said John Trussell, assistant director for the
Insurance Reserve Fund, which insures the stadium. ``But with only
six or eight games a year, it will fall down from old age long
before that.''
   Jerry T. Brewer, dean of student life, wrote to James K.
Copenhaver, director of university bands, that the Insurance Reserve
Fund has ``specifically mandated that `Louie, Louie' not be played.
I know this request may seem unusual to band directors, but a
`swaying' stadium is definitely not a usual occurrence.''
   Trussell, however, said the fund, which gets its marching orders
from the state, had not outlawed any songs.
   ``There's no provision in a policy saying, `Thou Shalt Not Play
Louie, Louie,'' he said.
</TEXT>
