<HEAD>Five Dead, 17 Injured In Hostel Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with 17 injured, more details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire blamed on arson swept through a
Sydney area hostel popular with overseas tourists early Sunday,
killing at least five people and injuring 17, an official said.
   The fire began shortly before 5 a.m. at the Down Under Hotel in
the suburb of Kings Cross.
   The five people who perished were in two bedrooms on the second
floor, a Fire Brigade spokesman said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. It was not known if any foreigners were among the dead.
   Two of the injured were reported in critical condition.
   Arson was suspected, the spokesman said. ``We don't believe it
started naturally,'' he told the Australian Associated Press.
   It was not known how many people were staying at the hostel when
the fire broke out, according to the spokesman. He said at least 60
people were rescued from the burning building and some saved
themselves by jumping from windows.
   Danish tourist Jan Martens told a radio interviewer he escaped
only in his underwear by climbing out of a window.
   The spokesman said there might be bodies still in the gutted
wreckage.
   Many of the injured were hospitalized with burns and smoke
inhalation, he said.
