<HEAD>Fans Do Without Umbrellas During Football Games</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Poppins and her pals are no longer
welcome at University of Oklahoma home football games _ now that
umbrellas are banned.
   Robert C. Connor, manager of athletic housing and facilities,
says spectators have been cooperative about the new Oklahoma
Memorial Stadium ban on umbrellas in the stadium during football
games.
   In fact, fans cheered and applauded during the first game of the
season, a rainy 73-3 blowout aginst New Mexico State, when the
announcement was made over the public address system, Connor said
Friday.
   The decision was made to ban the use of umbrellas at home games
because for liability reasons and because fans complained that the
umbrellas blocked their view, Connor said.
   ``Our primary concern was the liability that someone can get
poked in the eye,'' Connor said.
   The new policy was put to the test at Oklahoma's first two games,
which were both played under rainy skies, but it didn't create any
major problems, Connor said.
