<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0107EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Estonia-Brutality     09-16 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Estonia-Brutality,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brutal Soldiers Punished, But So is Journalist, Group Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A London-based movement for free speech said Friday
that three Soviet soldiers were punished for brutality, but the
Estonian journalist who helped expose the case was drafted into the
army in retaliation.
   The Index on Censorship organization appealed to supporters to
write to Soviet Defense Minister Dmitri Yazov and protest.
   It said Noorte Haal (Voice of Youth), journal of the Komsomol
Youth Communist League in Estonia, published an article on March 21
``about the appalling experiences in the Soviet army'' of ``Mati,''
a young Estonian conscript.
   It said ``brutality, degradation and corruption were starkly
revealed as well as the fact that Mati had traveled to Moscow to
describe his case and apply for a transfer.''
   It said authorities agreed to transfer him, but on Sept. 13 the
journalist, Madis Jurgen, was ordered to report for an army medical
examination in six days.
   Jurgen's report led to a trial that ended on Aug. 4 with one
soldier's being sentenced to four years in a labor camp and two
others to three years in a disciplinary battalion, it said.
   Index on Censorship said a company commander was forced to retire
and his political aide was reprimanded and transferred.
   ``The journalist, Madis Jurgen, will nevertheless be drafted for
exposing an illegality which led to the trial and conviction of at
least some of the guilty,'' it said.
   Index on Censorship did not identify the unit or give other
details about Mati, who came from Tallinn, capital of Estonia, or
Jurgen.
   The glasnost-era Soviet press has exposed widespread hazing of
recruits, poor living conditions in the barracks and other woes in
the Soviet armed forces, which once were above public reproach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890916-0158 </DOCNO>
