<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Refugees     09-16 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Refugees,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Refugees Dance to Their Arrival in West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two East German refugees who taught ballroom
dancing in their homeland fulfilled a lifelong dream Friday by
swirling around a dance floor at Blackpool, a mecca for their art.
   When Hans Georg Stelnig and his wife, Evelyn, crossed from
Hungary to Austria with thousands of other East Germans earlier this
week, he laughingly told television reporters, ``We are going to
Blackpool!''
   Devotees of ballroom dancing consider the English east coast
resort city to be a hotbed for that dance form.
   Britain's Independent Television News arranged to bring the
Stelnigs to Blackpool, where they were greeted with a bouquet and a
tour of the sights.
   They were also allowed to switch on the city's famous
``illuminations,'' lighting up the streets and buildings.
   He wore evening clothes and she sported a black and white polka
dot gown as they pulled the electric switch and giggled with delight
to see ``Welcome Hans Georg and Evelyn'' spelled out in lights.
   They later spun gracefully around a ballroom dance floor by
themselves while an orchestra played ``The Last Waltz.''
</TEXT>
