<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DisasterPayments     09-16 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disaster Payments,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Advancing Disaster Payment Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm-state senators said Friday they hoped the
Senate would act quickly on a committee proposal that could mean
larger disaster payments to winter wheat and cotton farmers who
started a second crop after weather destroyed their first.
   Legislation approved by the Senate Agriculture Committee Thursday
night would change the way disaster assistance payments are
calculated.
   Lawmakers have complained that an Agriculture Department formula
will penalize those producers, and in some instances mean farmers
could receive no disaster payments even though they earned little or
no profit on their second crops.
   The proposal is part of a broad budget-balancing package the
Senate is expected to consider soon, but some farm-state members
hope the disaster relief measure can be acted on separately.
   The problem stems from a nearly $900 million disaster relief
package enacted last month. In an effort to prevent farmers from
reaping double benefits, it required the department to reduce
assistance payments to farmers by the value of any crop that
replaced one ruined by bad weather.
   The legislation did not spell out how to determine the
replacement crop value. The department decided to deduct 75 percent
of the gross value of the replacement crop from the disaster payment
a farmer would have otherwise received for losses on his first crop.
   The formula is supposed to account for production costs of the
replacement crop, in effect coming up with a net value figure.
However, lawmakers contended the does not account for regional
differences in production costs.
   Under the Agriculture Committee proposal, farmers would have no
payment reductions if their replacement crops failed to produce more
than 40 percent of the average yield in their county. Those farmers
harvesting more than that would undergo the 75 percent deduction
only on the value of their replacement crops above the 40 percent
yield threshold.
   Other provisions would require quick payment for acres not
replanted, for which farmers would have to apply before Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890916-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     09-16 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peru, Mobil Agree on Search for Oil in Guerrilla, Drug Lands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and Mobil Oil signed a contract
Friday opening for exploration much of Peru's Upper Huallaga Valley,
a region largely under leftist rebel control and a focus of
President Bush's anti-drug strategy.
   The valley, 270 miles northeast of Lima, is the source of most of
the world's coca leaf, the raw material for making cocaine. Peruvian
police with help from U.S. drug agents are conducting raids there to
destroy labs operated by drug traffickers allied with the Maoist
Shining Path guerrillas.
   President Alan Garcia said the presence of Mobil in the Huallaga
Valley is a ``long-term way to combat subversion and to combat the
cultivation of coca.''
   Government officials and company representitives did not comment
on what security measures would be taken to protect Mobil workers.
   The agreement calls for an initial investment of $107.5 million
in the valley over the contract's six-year exploration phase and the
drilling of at least one exploratory well a year. More than 14,000
square miles of the valley will be open for exploration.
   The company is required to begin exploration work within 180 days.
   Mobil predicts a possible investment of $1.5 to $2 billion over
the 30-year extraction phase of the contract should exploration
prove fruitful.
   Daniel Nunez, president of the state-owned petroleum company
PetroPeru, which represents the government in the contract, said the
area could contain as much as 1 billion barrels of oil.
   The government estimates Peru's current oil reserves at about 440
million barrels. Peru produces about 140,000 barrels a day, of which
about 120,000 barrels are used domestically.
   The only other foreign oil company operating in Peru is
Occidental Petroleum, which has wells in the Amazon jungle near the
border with Ecuador.
</TEXT>
