<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--TrainExplosion     09-16 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Train Explosion,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical-Laden Train Car Explodes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LX12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chemical-laden train car exploded Friday
in a rail yard, breaking windows, injuring one man and prompting
evacuation of a west Louisville neighborhood, firefighters said.
   The car, a tanker composed of sealed compartments, was loaded
with calcium carbide, a powder that forms volatile acetylene gas
when mixed with water, officials said.
   At least two of the car's compartments remained intact, but an
evacuation was ordered because intermittent rain posed the threat of
more explosions, Louisville Fire Chief Russell Sanders said.
   The fire department's hazardous-materials unit eventually covered
the wreckage in plastic. Area residents were allowed back into their
houses after about two hours.
   A man was injured in the blast, but was conscious and talking to
rescuers as he was taken to Humana Hospital-University of
Louisville, Sanders said.
   A nursing supervisor at the hospital identified the victim as
Tracey Knight. She said his condition was stable and that he was
being treated in the emergency room, but that no other details could
be released.
</TEXT>
