<FIRST>r a AM-EthiopianTalks     09-16 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopian Talks,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopia, Eritrea to Pursue Peace Talks, But Agenda Issues Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia and the Eritrean People's Liberation
Front have agreed to meet in Africa to discuss an end to their
28-year-old war, but former President Jimmy Carter said Friday
``significant'' disagreements remain over the framework for the
talks.
   Carter said the two sides made progress in negotiations in
Atlanta to set an agenda for peace talks, agreeing on such items as
the official languages, publicity, recording and procedural rules
for the next talks.
   Still unresolved after a week of meetings at The Carter Center
are who would serve as co-chairmen for the peace talks, who would be
allowed as observers and what would be the duties of the meeting's
staff, Carter said.
   The talks would be held at one or more of these African nations:
North Yemen, Egypt, Sudan, Kenya, Tanzania and Zimbabwe. Carter said
no date for the peace talks has been set.
   Representatives of the Ethiopian government and the rebel EPLF
have met daily, except last Sunday, since Sept. 7 with Carter as a
neutral observer to draft an agenda for future, substantiative peace
talks.
   Carter is leaving Saturday for a three-day fact-finding mission
in Nicaragua, and the Ethiopia-EPLF talks here will conclude upon
his return Tuesday.
   Observers of African affairs had said at the outset of the
Atlanta talks that Carter had accomplished something by merely
getting Ethiopia and Eritrea to sit down together.
   Carter himself said he feared the animosity between the two sides
might doom the talks before any progress was made. But he told
reporters Friday both sides have gotten along well.
   ``I would tell you, the determination on both sides successfully
to resolve the differences that have caused the war has been very
obvious.''
   The leaders of the respective delegations _ Ashegre Yigletu, head
of the government Central Committee's Foreign Relations Department,
and Alamin Mohamed Saiyed, an EPLF Politburo member _ appeared with
Carter at the news conference but neither took questions from
reporters.
   Carter said he hoped a cease fire or an improvement in the
delivery of relief services in the region might be undertaken before
the peace talks, but he said he has not tried to suggest what either
side should do.
   He did not rule out the possibility that he would be involved in
the next round of talks, but said at least one co-chairman from
Africa must be selected before he would consider joining the talks.
   Ethiopia and the EPLF have been at war since 1961 over the
independence of Eritrea, a northern province in the Horn of Africa.
The two were joined in a federation that Eritrea opposed.
   An estimated 1 million people have been killed in the fighting
and famine directly related to the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
