<DOCNO> AP890916-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TentCity     09-16 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tent City,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Loses Bid To Close `Tent City' Saturday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge agreed Friday to block the state's
bid to close ``Tent City,'' the makeshift outdoor county prison camp
where 100 inmates have spent the last month, officials said.
   State corrections officials wanted Saturday to be the last day
for the Secaucus camp, opened as a court-ordered measure to relieve
severe overcrowding in the Hudson County jail.
   But the prisoners will stay at least another week under an order
by Judge Burrell Ives Humphrey in Superior Court in Hudson County.
   ``There is no way tent city is closing tomorrow,'' said Cas
Rakowski, a spokesman for the county jail. ``It would be a near
impossibility to take those 100 state prisoners.''
   Humphrey said the state cannot close the tent city without his
approval and without giving at least seven days notice, Rakowski
said.
   The state argued that it had satisfied the original court order
that forced the quick assemblage of tents and barbed wire on a site
in the Hackensack Meadowlands.
   State lawyers said the temporary order covered a 30-day period
ending Saturday, while county representatives said it was in force
long enough for them to complete the new jail, which is scheduled to
open Oct. 9.
   County officials say they cannot find room for the
minimum-security, Tent City inmates until they complete the
prefabricated, 336-bed jail at Kearny.
   The inmates are convicted of crimes that would have them in state
prisons if not for a backlog that has forced an overflow of
state-sentenced prisoners at the county jails.
   While the tent jail has been popular with inmates and has largely
been judged a success, Corrections Department spokesman James
Stabile said it would be unwise to start relying on such stopgap
measures in the future.
   ``This is a temporary measure,'' he said. ``Cold weather is
coming. It's worked with minimum security inmates, (but) it's not
something we wanted to do. It's something we had to do.''
   The inmates have praised the prison camp, saying its spaciousness
and fresh air are superior to the cramped quarters of the
overcrowded, 63-year-old Hudson County Jail, which has a population
near 900.
   ``Prisoners love it out there,'' Rakowski said. ``They have more
freedom, more recreation. ... It's like camp to them.''
</TEXT>
