<DATELINE>FREDERICTON, New Brunswick (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Colombians accused of drug
smuggling have been moved to a more secure prison after being linked
to five heavily armed South Americans who were arrested near the
Maine border, officials said.
   Authorities on Friday declined to say if the five men, arrested
Wednesday, had planned to interfere with court proceedings for the
Colombians.
   But asked if the two cases were related, Inspector Al Hutchinson
of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Fredericton said, ``That's
correct.''
   ``We've re-evaluated the situation between the two groups,'' he
said without elaborating.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a sun-drenched day, Exxon pulled out its
cleanup crews for the winter and the state announced its own plan to
protect fish hatcheries and untainted areas from the Exxon Valdez
oil spill.
   ``It's a nice day for the first day of winter, isn't it?'' Gov.
Steve Cowper said Friday before he announced the state's plans for a
$21 million program ``to continue cleanup work left by Exxon.''
   But for that bit of sarcasm, and a crack by his spokesman about a
``dirty dozen of soiled beaches'' left by Exxon, Cowper was
conciliatory toward the oil company responsible for the March 24
tanker wreck that left 10.9 million gallons of crude oil in Prince
William Sound.
   The governor thanked the thousands of workers who helped scrub
the oil-fouled shorelines, proclaiming Friday ``Oil Spill Workers
Appreciation Day'' in Alaska.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients worried they may be infected with the
AIDS virus will be able to get a quick and confidential answer soon
with a simple test that takes only 10 minutes.
   The test, now undergoing trials at nine centers, will enable
people to get results quickly in a doctor's office instead of having
to wait to hear from a distant laboratory.
   ``It provides a new means for patients to learn of their AIDS
status and still retain anonymity,'' said Jarel R. Kelsey, president
of Murex Corp., a Norcross, Ga., firm that developed the test.
``Once this method is widely available, it will encourage more
people to determine their status.''
   Tests for AIDS now require that blood be drawn and sent to a
laboratory for complex processing. Patients must wait to find out if
they have contracted the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, which
causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome, or AIDS.
</TEXT>
