<FIRST>d f PM-GeorgiaGulf     09-16 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Georgia Gulf,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>NL Industries Changing Tactics on Georgia Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies controlled by billionaire Texas
investor Harold C. Simmons are cutting their stake in Georgia Gulf
Corp. and putting on hold a plan to oust the chemical concern's
board.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission on Friday
, the Dallas-based Simmons consortium _ headed by NL Industries Inc.
_ said it was cutting its Georgia Gulf holdings to 8.9 percent of
common stock outstanding.
   NL also said it wants to work with Georgia Gulf in its ``pursuit
of alternative transactions.''
   Previously, NL Industries said it would seek written consents
from shareholders to oust the board after it rejected an offer to
acquire the Atlanta-based company or help it recapitalize, which
would give shareholders at least $55 per share in cash.
   No further meetings between NL and Georgia Gulf are scheduled,
the SEC filing said.
   Georgia Gulf's board announced on Thursday that it had asked
investment banking firm Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. to explore alternative
transactions such as an acquisition or joint venture.
   Meanwhile, NL Industries and another Simmons affilate, NL
Chemicals Inc., have sold off 230,000 Georgia Gulf shares over the
last two weeks, cutting their holdings from 9.9 to 8.9 percent. NL
controls 5.6 percent of Georgia Gulf's outstanding common stock,
whicle NL Chemicals has 3.3 percent.
   The shares were sold in blocks ranging from 6,300 shares to
33,500 shares for prices between $58.50 and $59.50 per share.
   The two Simmons companies said they will continue selling shares
if they stay above the $55 price they believe could be obtained
through leveraged recapitalization, merger or other transaction.
   But NL and NLC also said they would resume their dump-the-board
plan in Georgia Gulf takes steps ``not reasonably calculated to
realize'' at least $55 per share for stockholders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
