<DOCNO> AP890916-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-89 0612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-Brady-NASD     09-16 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brady-NASD,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary: Junk Bond Shakeup Won't Affect Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady says
investors shouldn't be worried about price drops in the junk bond
market spreading to the stock market.
   ``I don't think that's going to happen,'' Brady told a luncheon
marking the 50th anniversary of the National Association of
Securities Dealers on Friday.
   Brady also defended the proposed cut in capital gains taxes but
said he favored a reduction longer the 27 months contained in a
House bill that passed through committee this week.
   The market in high-yield, high-risk bonds has been in tailspin
since Wednesday, when retailing giant Campeau Corp. said it might
not be able to make a major loan payment for one of its affiliates
to avoid defaulting on its junk bond debt.
   Since then, panicky investors have dumped issues they deemed
especially risky.
   But Brady said junk bonds ``have a substantial assets base. This
isn't just equity in disguise. There literally are assets behind
it.''
   ``So I don't think it'll have an effect on the stock market,'' he
added.
   After a brief speech, Brady answered several questions at the
luncheon for NASD, the self-regulatory group that oversees the
over-the-counter market of securities that aren't traded on nation's
major stock exchanges.
   He defended the proposed cut in capital gains _ profits from the
sale of capital assets such as stocks or real estate _ approved by
the House Ways and Means Committee on Thursday. The plan still must
clear the full House as well as the Senate.
   The plan approved by the committee would reduce the tax rate of
33 percent to 19.6 percent for the next 27 months. The tax rate then
would rise to 28 percent but would be ``indexed'' to tax only
increases exceeding the annual inflation rate.
   Brady said he wished the terms of the proposed tax were longer,
``but let's take what we can get and keep working on it,'' he said.
   Critics have called it a tax break for the rich, while supporters
say it would help the economy by encouraging investment.
   ``People are beginning to understand that this not only benefits
people who are in our industry, purchasing and selling securities,''
Brady told the crowd of about 300 stock and bond dealers, industry
regulators and reporters.
   ``It benefits the guy who who starts a steel distribution
business, with his $10,000 savings, in his garage and 38 years later
sells it to somebody else for 750,000 bucks,'' he said. ``They're
starting to understand that this isn't some sort of Wall Street
benefit plan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
